arts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=40275 |accessdate= 12 July 2014}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|21\n|-\n|Canada ([[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'' Top 100 Singles]])<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.0619&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=u9874ano8k0c5b6bkp4r8qrbp3 |title= Top Singles \u2013 Volume 43, No. 16, December 28 1985 |work= [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] |publisher= [[Library and Archives Canada]] |accessdate= 12 July 2014}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|18\n|-\n|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref>{{cite web|title= Top 100 Hits for 1985 |publisher= The Longbored Surfer |accessdate= 12 July 2014 |url= http://longboredsurfer.com/charts/1985.php}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|75\n|-\n|US [[Cashbox (magazine)|''Cash Box'']]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/80s_files/1985YESP.html |title= The CASH BOX Year-End Charts: 1985 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121001214739/http://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/80s_files/1985YESP.html |archivedate= 1 October 2012}}. ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]''.</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|80\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|type=single|region=Canada|artist=Katrina and the Waves|title=Walking on sunshine|award=Gold|digital=true|certyear=1985|relyear=1985|accessdate=22 June 2018}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|type=single|region=Denmark|artist=Katrina & the Waves|title=Walking on Sunshine|award=Gold|certyear=2019|relyear=1985|id=8457|accessdate=21 September 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|type=single|region=Italy|artist=Katrina & the Waves|title=Walking on Sunshine|award=Gold|certyear=2018|relyear=1985|accessdate=3 September 2018}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|type=single|region=United Kingdom|artist=Katrina & the Waves|title=Walking on Sunshine|award=Platinum|certyear=2020|relyear=2005|id=13370-4062-1|accessdate=11 January 2020}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|streaming=true}}\n\n==Dolly Parton version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Walking on Sunshine\n| cover      = DollyWalkingOnSunshine.jpeg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Dolly Parton]]\n| album      = [[Treasures (Dolly Parton album)|Treasures]]\n| released   = 1999\n| format     = [[Maxi single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 3:12\n| label      =\n*Rising Tide\n*Blue Eye\n| writer     = [[Kimberley Rew]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Just When I Needed You Most]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = Peace Train\n| next_year  = 1997\n}}\n\nIn 1996, [[Dolly Parton]] included a version of \"Walking on Sunshine\" on her album of covers, ''[[Treasures (Dolly Parton album)|Treasures]],'' stating in interviews to promote the album, as well as her [[CBS]] TV special to promote the album, that she had long loved the song. In 1997, a dance remix of Parton's version was released.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Aly & AJ cover==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Walking on Sunshine\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Aly & AJ]]\n| album      = [[Into the Rush]] and [[Herbie: Fully Loaded#Soundtrack|Herbie: Fully Loaded soundtrack]]\n| released   = 2005\n| format     = [[Radio Disney]] single\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 3:54\n| label      = [[Hollywood Records]]\n| writer     = [[Kimberley Rew]]\n| producer   = [[Matthew Gerrard]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n[[Matthew Gerrard]] produced a cover of \"Walking on Sunshine\" for American [[pop rock]] duo [[Aly & AJ]]'s debut album, ''[[Into the Rush]]''. The song was released as the album's fourth single on June 22, 2005 (see [[2005 in music]]). It was also used to promote the film ''[[Herbie: Fully Loaded]]'' and makes an appearance on the [[Herbie: Fully Loaded (soundtrack)|movie soundtrack]]. The single's video features Aly & AJ performing and is intercut with clips from the film ''Herbie: Fully Loaded''. The song was shortened down to one minute and 55 seconds (1:55), as it is used for the video. This song was also featured in the 2010 film ''[[Ramona and Beezus]]'' and the 2011 film ''[[Sharpay's Fabulous Adventure]]''.\n\n===Track listings===\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = Radio Disney Promo CD<ref>{{cite web|title= Walking on Sunshine ~ Release by Aly & AJ |publisher= [[MusicBrainz]] |accessdate= 12 July 2014 |url= http://musicbrainz.org/release/56710ef6-6aa7-4c40-a69b-173409acdd75}}</ref>\n| title1          = Walking on Sunshine\n| writer1         = Kimberly Rew\n| length1         = 3:54\n}}\n\n===Release history===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Date\n!Country\n!Format\n!Label\n|-\n|22 June 2005\n|United States\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Promo CD\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Hollywood Records]]\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Date\n!Country\n!Format\n!Label\n|-\n|6 February 2006\n|United Kingdom\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Promo CD\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Squirrel Records]]\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Appearances in popular culture==\n<!-- None of the individual sightings are sourced. Please don't add more without including a source; and if you have a real source (not IMDB, which is reader-populated like Wikipedia) for any already here, please add. -->\nThe song is very popular in commercials, and advertisers typically pay $150,000 to $200,000 per year to use the song.<ref name=\"NPR\"/>\n* In September 2010, the cast of ''[[Ni Hao, Kai-Lan]]'' and [[Colbie Callat]] cpveed the song as part of the ''Nickelodeon/NOGGIN Mega Music Festival''. The animation was released seperately on select Nick Jr DVDs and a few Nick Jr commercial break airtimes.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{MetroLyrics song|aly-aj|walking-on-sunshine|version=Aly & AJ version}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Katrina and the Waves}}\n{{78violet}}\n\n[[Category:1983 songs]]\n[[Category:1985 singles]]\n[[Category:1997 singles]]\n[[Category:2005 singles]]\n[[Category:Katrina and the Waves songs]]\n[[Category:Aly & AJ songs]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records singles]]\n[[Category:Hollywood Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kimberley Rew]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walking_on_Sunshine_(Katrina_and_the_Waves_song)"}
{"title_page": "Yadlin affair", "text_new": "The '''Yadlin affair''' ({{lang-he|\u05e4\u05e8\u05e9\u05ea \u05d9\u05d3\u05dc\u05d9\u05df}}, ''Parashat Yadlin'') was a [[political corruption]] scandal that broke in [[Israel]] in 1976, involving senior members of the [[Labor Party (Israel)|Labor Party]] (then the major faction in the [[Alignment (political party)|Alignment]]). It is often seen as one of the reasons for the \"revolution\" of the [[1977 Israeli legislative election|1977 elections]].\n\n==Background==\nIn 1976, ''[[HaOlam HaZeh]]'' began publishing investigations regarding illegitimate financial transactions concerning senior members of the labor movement and the party funds. The names mentioned included [[Asher Yadlin]], who was about to be appointed Governor of the [[Bank of Israel]]. Yadlin was known to be a gambling buff (favoring the [[Las Vegas Strip|Las Vegas]] roulette table) with an eye for pretty women, He was also a major fund raiser for the [[Labor Party (Israel)|Labor Party]]; since 1973, he had headed Israel's huge [[Clalit|Kupat Holim]] health-insurance program.<ref name=\"time\">{{cite news\n| title = Cabinet Fratricide\n| publisher = [[Time (magazine)|TIME]]\n| accessdate = 2007-12-28\n| date = November 8, 1976\n| url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,918489,00.html?promoid=googlep\n}}</ref> The reports also mentioned [[Avraham Ofer]], [[Yitzhak Rabin]]'s [[Housing Minister of Israel|Minister of Housing]]. The investigations suggested bribery, and the reporter [[Yigal Laviv]] pressed charges.\n\n==Scandal==\nThe [[Cabinet of Israel|cabinet]] decided, on September 5, to appoint Yadlin, former head of the [[Histadrut]]'s economic enterprises, governor of the Bank of Israel to succeed [[Moshe Sanbar]] on November 1. On the day after the cabinet decision, [[Internal Security Minister of Israel|Police Minister]] [[Shlomo Hillel]] and Attorney-General [[Aharon Barak]] were informed that the police had been inquiring into allegations against Yadlin of improper conduct in the management of Kupat Holim. Yadlin declared that the allegations were without basis and that he would welcome an investigation.<ref name=\"karlikow\">{{cite web|last=Karlikow|first=Abraham|title=Israel|work=American Jewish Yearbook|year=1978|accessdate=2007-12-28|url=http://www.ajcarchives.org/AJC_DATA/Files/1978_12_IsraelArab.pdf}}</ref>\n\nAfter a month of intensive police investigation, Yadlin was detained for interrogation on suspicion of having accepted bribes and undercover commissions in transactions affecting Kupat Holim. On October 24 the cabinet resolved, without prejudging the charges against Yadlin, that it could no longer delay the appointment, and named Director-General of the Treasury [[Arnon Gafni]] as governor of the Bank of Israel.<ref name=\"karlikow\" />\n\nThere was considerable criticism of the daily publicity by the press to unproven rumors of charges against Yadlin, which were believed to have been fed by unauthorized disclosures from police sources. In mid-December Yadlin was charged with taking bribes totaling [[Israeli lira|I\u00a3]] 280,000, as well as other offenses, and was remanded in custody until his trial.<ref name=\"knesset\">{{cite web\n| title = History of the Eighth Knesset | publisher=The [[Knesset]]\n| accessdate = 2007-12-28\n| url = https://www.knesset.gov.il/history/eng/eng_hist8.htm\n}}</ref> On March 14, 1977, Yadlin pleaded guilty to some of the charges, involving bribes totaling I\u00a3124,000, but claimed that he had handed over\nI\u00a380,000 of the money to Labor party funds, adding that he had raised \"millions\" for the party. The judge did not accept his claim and sentenced him to five years' imprisonment and a fine of I\u00a3250,000. Further charges were to be investigated by the police after consideration of Yadlin's appeal.<ref name=\"karlikow\" />\n\n==Aftermath==\nTowards the upcoming elections, [[Shimon Peres]] and his supporters had jumped on the Yadlin scandal as proof of Rabin's poor judgment in making appointments. For the left, it showed that the Labor Party had lost track of its ideological [[socialism|socialist]] roots.<ref name=\"brenner\">{{cite web\n| last = Brenner\n| first = Lenni\n| title = The 29 Years in the Desert\n| work = The Iron Wall\n| accessdate = 2007-12-28\n| url = http://www.marxists.org/history/etol/document/mideast/ironwall/13-desert.htm\n}}</ref> For the Israeli right, it was evidence of the Labor Party's corruptibility.<ref name=\"likud1\" /> It is widely regarded as one of the main causes of the [[Labor Party (Israel)|Labor party]]'s downfall in the elections.\n\nYadlin was released from prison in 1981 and subsequently emigrated to the [[United States]]. [[Talia Livni]], Yadlin's [[common law wife]], was a lawyer who assisted him in legal matters. She married him while he was in jail, but divorced him after he emigrated. Dalia, Yadlin's ex-wife, supported him and tried to present him as a pawn in the party's hands and as a victim of its \"method\".\n\nOfer, whose name was associated with the Yadlin affair as well as another one, committed suicide on January 3, 1977.\n\nBarak was seen as a relentless fighter against corruption. He was later appointed to the [[Supreme Court of Israel]]. Some argue that his role in the Yadlin affair helped him carry out his famous [[judicial activist]] positions.<ref name=\"dar\">{{cite web\n| last = Der\n| first = Yossi\n| title = Aharon Barak and the Buzaglo Test\n| publisher = [[NFC (news)|NFC]]\n| accessdate = 2007-12-28\n| url = http://www.nfc.co.il/Archive/003-D-18337-00.html?tag=16-11-24\n|language=he}}</ref>\n\nThe \"Yadlin House\", a building in north [[Tel Aviv]], whose construction was linked to the bribe money, remained unfinished. In 2005 it was sold and has since been demolished.<ref name=\"aviv\">{{cite news\n| title = Yadlin House will be Demolished in Favor of Aviv BeGimel Neighborhood\n| date=March 15, 2005\n| publisher=[[Ynet]]\n| accessdate = 2007-12-28\n| url = http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-3058590,00.html\n|language=he}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"likud1\">{{cite web\n| title = Yadlin Affair\n| publisher=Likud1\n| accessdate = 2007-12-28\n| url = http://likud1.ios.st/Front/Newsnet/reports.asp?reportId=4660\n|language=he}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nrg.co.il/online/archive/ART/276/334.html Yadlin Affair, 1975] Maariv, 17 December 2007 {{in lang|he}}\n\n[[Category:Political scandals in Israel]]\n[[Category:1976 in Israeli politics]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Yadlin affair''' ({{lang-he|\u05e4\u05e8\u05e9\u05ea \u05d9\u05d3\u05dc\u05d9\u05df}}, ''Parashat Yadlin'') was a [[political corruption]] scandal that broke in [[Israel]] in 1976, involving senior members of the [[Labor Party (Israel)|Labor Party]] (then the major faction in the [[Alignment (political party)|Alignment]]). It is often seen as one of the reasons for the \"revolution\" of the [[1977 Israeli legislative election|1977 elections]].\n\n==Background==\nIn 1976, [[Haolam Hazeh]] began publishing investigations regarding illegitimate financial transactions concerning senior members of the labor movement and the party funds. The names mentioned included [[Asher Yadlin]], who was about to be appointed Governor of the [[Bank of Israel]]. Yadlin was known to be a gambling buff (favoring the [[Las Vegas Strip|Las Vegas]] roulette table) with an eye for pretty women, He was also a major fund raiser for the [[Labor Party (Israel)|Labor Party]]; since 1973, he had headed Israel's huge [[Clalit|Kupat Holim]] health-insurance program.<ref name=\"time\">{{cite news\n| title = Cabinet Fratricide\n| publisher = [[Time (magazine)|TIME]]\n| accessdate = 2007-12-28\n| date = November 8, 1976\n| url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,918489,00.html?promoid=googlep\n}}</ref> The reports also mentioned [[Avraham Ofer]], [[Yitzhak Rabin]]'s [[Housing Minister of Israel|Minister of Housing]]. The investigations suggested bribery, and the reporter [[Yigal Laviv]] pressed charges.\n\n==Scandal==\nThe [[Cabinet of Israel|cabinet]] decided, on September 5, to appoint Yadlin, former head of the [[Histadrut]]'s economic enterprises, governor of the Bank of Israel to succeed [[Moshe Sanbar]] on November 1. On the day after the cabinet decision, [[Internal Security Minister of Israel|Police Minister]] [[Shlomo Hillel]] and Attorney-General [[Aharon Barak]] were informed that the police had been inquiring into allegations against Yadlin of improper conduct in the management of Kupat Holim. Yadlin declared that the allegations were without basis and that he would welcome an investigation.<ref name=\"karlikow\">{{cite web|last=Karlikow|first=Abraham|title=Israel|work=American Jewish Yearbook|year=1978|accessdate=2007-12-28|url=http://www.ajcarchives.org/AJC_DATA/Files/1978_12_IsraelArab.pdf}}</ref>\n\nAfter a month of intensive police investigation, Yadlin was detained for interrogation on suspicion of having accepted bribes and undercover commissions in transactions affecting Kupat Holim. On October 24 the cabinet resolved, without prejudging the charges against Yadlin, that it could no longer delay the appointment, and named Director-General of the Treasury [[Arnon Gafni]] as governor of the Bank of Israel.<ref name=\"karlikow\" />\n\nThere was considerable criticism of the daily publicity by the press to unproven rumors of charges against Yadlin, which were believed to have been fed by unauthorized disclosures from police sources. In mid-December Yadlin was charged with taking bribes totaling [[Israeli lira|I\u00a3]] 280,000, as well as other offenses, and was remanded in custody until his trial.<ref name=\"knesset\">{{cite web\n| title = History of the Eighth Knesset | publisher=The [[Knesset]]\n| accessdate = 2007-12-28\n| url = https://www.knesset.gov.il/history/eng/eng_hist8.htm\n}}</ref> On March 14, 1977, Yadlin pleaded guilty to some of the charges, involving bribes totaling I\u00a3124,000, but claimed that he had handed over\nI\u00a380,000 of the money to Labor party funds, adding that he had raised \"millions\" for the party. The judge did not accept his claim and sentenced him to five years' imprisonment and a fine of I\u00a3250,000. Further charges were to be investigated by the police after consideration of Yadlin's appeal.<ref name=\"karlikow\" />\n\n==Aftermath==\nTowards the upcoming elections, [[Shimon Peres]] and his supporters had jumped on the Yadlin scandal as proof of Rabin's poor judgment in making appointments. For the left, it showed that the Labor Party had lost track of its ideological [[socialism|socialist]] roots.<ref name=\"brenner\">{{cite web\n| last = Brenner\n| first = Lenni\n| title = The 29 Years in the Desert\n| work = The Iron Wall\n| accessdate = 2007-12-28\n| url = http://www.marxists.org/history/etol/document/mideast/ironwall/13-desert.htm\n}}</ref> For the Israeli right, it was evidence of the Labor Party's corruptibility.<ref name=\"likud1\" /> It is widely regarded as one of the main causes of the [[Labor Party (Israel)|Labor party]]'s downfall in the elections.\n\nYadlin was released from prison in 1981 and subsequently emigrated to the [[United States]]. [[Talia Livni]], Yadlin's [[common law wife]], was a lawyer who assisted him in legal matters. She married him while he was in jail, but divorced him after he emigrated. Dalia, Yadlin's ex-wife, supported him and tried to present him as a pawn in the party's hands and as a victim of its \"method\".\n\nOfer, whose name was associated with the Yadlin affair as well as another one, committed suicide on January 3, 1977.\n\nBarak was seen as a relentless fighter against corruption. He was later appointed to the [[Supreme Court of Israel]]. Some argue that his role in the Yadlin affair helped him carry out his famous [[judicial activist]] positions.<ref name=\"dar\">{{cite web\n| last = Der\n| first = Yossi\n| title = Aharon Barak and the Buzaglo Test\n| publisher = [[NFC (news)|NFC]]\n| accessdate = 2007-12-28\n| url = http://www.nfc.co.il/Archive/003-D-18337-00.html?tag=16-11-24\n|language=he}}</ref>\n\nThe \"Yadlin House\", a building in north [[Tel Aviv]], whose construction was linked to the bribe money, remained unfinished. In 2005 it was sold and has since been demolished.<ref name=\"aviv\">{{cite news\n| title = Yadlin House will be Demolished in Favor of Aviv BeGimel Neighborhood\n| date=March 15, 2005\n| publisher=[[Ynet]]\n| accessdate = 2007-12-28\n| url = http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-3058590,00.html\n|language=he}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"likud1\">{{cite web\n| title = Yadlin Affair\n| publisher=Likud1\n| accessdate = 2007-12-28\n| url = http://likud1.ios.st/Front/Newsnet/reports.asp?reportId=4660\n|language=he}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nrg.co.il/online/archive/ART/276/334.html Yadlin Affair, 1975] Maariv, 17 December 2007 {{in lang|he}}\n\n[[Category:Political scandals in Israel]]\n[[Category:1976 in Israeli politics]]\n", "name_user": "Jprg1966", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yadlin_affair"}
{"title_page": "Plasmablastic lymphoma", "text_new": "'''Plasmablastic lymphoma''' (PBL) is a type of [[large B-cell lymphoma]] recognized by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) in 2017 as belonging to a subgroup of lymphomas termed [[lymphoid neoplasms with plasmablastic differentiation]]. The other lymphoid neoplasms within this subgroup are: [[Epstein-Barr virus-associated lymphoproliferative diseases#Epstein\u2013Barr virus-associated plasma cell|plasmablastic plasma cell lymphoma]] (or [[Epstein-Barr virus-associated lymphoproliferative diseases#Epstein\u2013Barr virus-associated plasma cell| plasmacytoma]]); [[Primary effusion lymphoma|primary effusion lymphoma, human herpes virus-positive or human herpes virus-negative]]; [[ALK+ large B-cell lymphoma|anaplastic lymphoma kinase-positive large B-cell lymphoma]]; and [[HHV-8-associated MCD|human herpesvirus 8-positive diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, not otherwise specified]]. All of these lymphomas are malignancies of plasmablasts, i.e. [[B-cells]] that have [[differentiated]] into plasmablasts but because of their [[malignant]] nature: fail to differentiate further into mature [[plasma cells]]; proliferate excessively; and accumulate in and injure various tissues and organs.<ref name=\"pmid31725418\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Chen BJ, Chuang SS | title = Lymphoid Neoplasms With Plasmablastic Differentiation: A Comprehensive Review and Diagnostic Approaches | journal = Advances in Anatomic Pathology | volume = 27 | issue = 2 | pages = 61\u201374 | date = March 2020 | pmid = 31725418 | doi = 10.1097/PAP.0000000000000253 | url = }}</ref>\n\nThe lymphomas in the lymphoid neoplasms with plasmablastic differentiation sub-group that are not PBL have sometimes been incorrectly considered to be variants of PBL. Each of the lymphomas in this subgroup of [[malignancies]] have distinctive clinical, morphological, and abnormal gene features. However, key features of these lymphomas sometime overlap with other lymphomas including those that are in this sub-group. In consequence, correctly diagnosing these lymphomas has been challenging.<ref name=\"pmid31360094\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Lopez A, Abrisqueta P | title = Plasmablastic lymphoma: current perspectives | journal = Blood and Lymphatic Cancer : Targets and Therapy | volume = 8 | issue = | pages = 63\u201370 | date = 2018 | pmid = 31360094 | pmc = 6467349 | doi = 10.2147/BLCTT.S142814 | url = }}</ref> Nonetheless, it is particularly important to diagnose them correctly because they can have very different prognoses and treatments than the lymphomas which they resemble.<ref name=\"pmid31725418\"/>  \n\nPlasmablastic lymphomas are aggressive and rare malignancies that usually respond poorly to [[chemotherapy]] and carry a very poor prognosis. They occur predominantly in males who have [[HIV/AIDS]], had a [[Organ transplantation|solid organ transplant]], or are [[Immunosuppression|immunosuppressed]] in other ways; ~5% of all individuals with PBL appear to be [[immunocompetent]], i.e. to have no apparent defect in their [[immune system]].<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/> The malignant plasmablasts in more than half the cases of PBL are infected with a potentially cancer-causing virus, [[Epstein Barr virus]] (EBV), and rare cases of PBL appear due to the  plasmablastic transformation of a preexisting low-grade [[B-cell lymphoma]].<ref name=\"pmid27271843\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Korkolopoulou P, Vassilakopoulos T, Milionis V, Ioannou M | title = Recent Advances in Aggressive Large B-cell Lymphomas: A Comprehensive Review | journal = Advances in Anatomic Pathology | volume = 23 | issue = 4 | pages = 202\u201343 | date = July 2016 | pmid = 27271843 | doi = 10.1097/PAP.0000000000000117 | url = }}</ref> One variant of PBL, sometimes termed '''plasmablastic lymphoma of the elderly,''' has a significantly better prognosis than most other cases of PBL.<ref name=\"pmid22958176\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Liu F, Asano N, Tatematsu A, Oyama T, Kitamura K, Suzuki K, Yamamoto K, Sakamoto N, Taniwaki M, Kinoshita T, Nakamura S | title = Plasmablastic lymphoma of the elderly: a clinicopathological comparison with age-related Epstein-Barr virus-associated B cell lymphoproliferative disorder | journal = Histopathology | volume = 61 | issue = 6 | pages = 1183\u201397 | date = December 2012 | pmid = 22958176 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2559.2012.04339.x | url = }}</ref> The development of this variant appears due, at least in part, to [[immunosenescence]], i.e. the immunodeficiency occurring in old age.<ref name=\"pmid27271843\"/>   \n\n== History ==\nA study by Green and Eversole published in 1989<ref name=\"pmid2542861\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Green TL, Eversole LR | title = Oral lymphomas in HIV-infected patients: association with Epstein-Barr virus DNA | journal = Oral Surgery, Oral Medicine, and Oral Pathology | volume = 67 | issue = 4 | pages = 437\u201342 | date = April 1989 | pmid = 2542861 | doi = 10.1016/0030-4220(89)90388-5 | url = }}</ref> reported on 9 individuals afflicted with HIV/AIDS who \npresented with lymphomatous masses in the oral cavity; these lymphomas were populated by apparently malignant Epstein-Barr virus-infected plasmablasts that did not express [[T-cell]] lymphocyte marker proteins. Eight years later, Delecluse and colleagues<ref name=\"pmid9028965\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Delecluse HJ, Anagnostopoulos I, Dallenbach F, Hummel M, Marafioti T, Schneider U, Huhn D, Schmidt-Westhausen A, Reichart PA, Gross U, Stein H | title = Plasmablastic lymphomas of the oral cavity: a new entity associated with the human immunodeficiency virus infection | journal = Blood | volume = 89 | issue = 4 | pages = 1413\u201320 | date = February 1997 | pmid = 9028965 | doi = | url = }}</ref> described a lymphoma, which they termed plasmablastic lymphoma, that had some features of a [[diffuse large B-cell lymphoma]] but unlike this lymphoma developed exclusively in the oral cavity, consisted of plasmablasts that lacked B-cell as well as T cell marker proteins and, in 15 of 16 cases, were infected with EBV. In 2008, the World Health Organization recognized this lymphoma as a variant of the diffuse large cell lymphomas.<ref name=\"pmid29917262\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Rodrigues-Fernandes CI, de Souza LL, ((Santos-Costa SFD)), ((Silva AMB)), ((Pontes HAR)), Lopes MA, de Almeida OP, Brennan PA, Fonseca FP | title = Clinicopathological analysis of oral plasmablastic lymphoma: A systematic review | journal = Journal of Oral Pathology & Medicine : Official Publication of the International Association of Oral Pathologists and the American Academy of Oral Pathology | volume = 47 | issue = 10 | pages = 915\u2013922 | date = November 2018 | pmid = 29917262 | doi = 10.1111/jop.12753 | url = }}</ref> Subsequent to this recognition, numerous studies found this lymphoma to occur in a wide range of tissues besides the oral cavity and in individuals with various other predisposing immunodeficiency conditions.<ref name=\"pmid32269975\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Li YJ, Li JW, Chen KL, Li J, Zhong MZ, Liu XL, Yi PY, Zhou H | title = HIV-negative plasmablastic lymphoma: report of 8 cases and a comprehensive review of 394 published cases | journal = Blood Research | volume = 55 | issue = 1 | pages = 49\u201356 | date = March 2020 | pmid = 32269975 | doi = 10.5045/br.2020.55.1.49 | url = }}</ref> In 2017, this Organization classified PBL as the most common member of a rare subgroup of lymphomas termed lymphoid neoplasms with plasmablastic differentiation.<ref name=\"pmid31725418\"/>  \n\n== Pathopysiology ==\nIn addition to the immunodeficiency-causing viral disease, HIV/AIDS (which is an [[AIDS-defining clinical condition]]<ref name=\"pmid29518976\"/>), recent studies have diagnosed PBL in individuals who have one or more other causes for immunodeficiency.<ref name=\"pmid32269975\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Li YJ, Li JW, Chen KL, Li J, Zhong MZ, Liu XL, Yi PY, Zhou H | title = HIV-negative plasmablastic lymphoma: report of 8 cases and a comprehensive review of 394 published cases | journal = Blood Research | volume = 55 | issue = 1 | pages = 49\u201356 | date = March 2020 | pmid = 32269975 | doi = 10.5045/br.2020.55.1.49 | url = }}</ref> These causes include prior organ transplantation; [[immunosuppressive drug]]s; [[Autoimmune disease|autoimmune ]] and [[Inflammation#Inflammatory disorders|chronic inflammatory diseases]] (e.g. [[hepatitis C]]<ref name=\"pmid27271843\"/>, [[rheumatoid arthritis]], [[Graves' disease]], [[Giant-cell arteritis]], [[sarcoidosis]], and severe [[psoriasis]]<ref name=\"pmid28031174\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Tchernonog E, Faurie P, Coppo P, Monjanel H, Bonnet A, Algarte G\u00e9nin M, Mercier M, Dupuis J, Bijou F, Herbaux C, Delmer A, Fabiani B, Besson C, Le Gouill S, Gyan E, Laurent C, Ghesquieres H, Cartron G | title = Clinical characteristics and prognostic factors of plasmablastic lymphoma patients: analysis of 135 patients from the LYSA group | journal = Annals of Oncology | volume = 28 | issue = 4 | pages = 843\u2013848 | date = April 2017 | pmid = 28031174 | doi = 10.1093/annonc/mdw684 | url = }}</ref>); and immunosenescence due to age (e.g. >60 years). Rare cases of PDL have also occurred as a transformation of a low grade B-cell malignancy such as [[Chronic lymphocytic leukemia|chronic lymphocytic leukemia/small lymphocytic lymphoma]] and [[follicular lymphoma]].<ref name=\"pmid27687004\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Montes-Moreno S, Martinez-Magunacelaya N, Zecchini-Barrese T, Villambros\u00eda SG, Linares E, Ranchal T, Rodriguez-Pinilla M, Batlle A, Cereceda-Company L, Revert-Arce JB, Almaraz C, Piris MA | title = Plasmablastic lymphoma phenotype is determined by genetic alterations in MYC and PRDM1 | journal = Modern Pathology : an Official Journal of the United States and Canadian Academy of Pathology, Inc | volume = 30 | issue = 1 | pages = 85\u201394 | date = January 2017 | pmid = 27687004 | doi = 10.1038/modpathol.2016.162 | url = }}</ref> Studies also find that 60-75% of individuals diagnosed with PBL have [[Epstein-Barr virus]]-infected plasmablasts.<ref name=\"pmid31725418\"/> EBV infects ~95% of the world's population to cause [[asymptomatic|no symptoms]], minor [[non-specific symptoms]], or [[infectious mononucleosis]]. The [[virus]] then enters a [[Virus latency|latency]] phase in which infected individuals become lifetime [[asymptomatic carrier]]s of the virus in a set of their B-cells. Some weeks, months, years, or decades thereafter, a very small fraction of these carriers, particularly those with an [[immunodeficiency]], develop any one of various EBV-associated benign or [[malignant]] diseases, including, in extremely rare cases, [[Epstein\u2013Barr virus-associated lymphoproliferative diseases#Epstein\u2013Barr virus-positive plasmablastic lymphoma|Epstein\u2013Barr virus-positive plasmablastic lymphoma]].<ref name=\"pmid29885408\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Rezk SA, Zhao X, Weiss LM | title = Epstein\u2014Barr virus-associated lymphoid proliferations, a 2018 update | journal = Human Pathology | volume = 79| issue = | pages = 18\u201341| date = June 2018 | pmid = 29885408 | doi = 10.1016/j.humpath.2018.05.020 | url = }}</ref> The virus in infected plasmablastic cells appears to be in its [[Epstein-Barr virus-associated lymphoproliferative diseases#Epstein\u2013Barr virus infection|latency I phase]]; consequently, these infected cells express EBV products such as [[EBER]] [[Small nuclear RNA|nuclear RNAs]] and [[mir-BART2 microRNA precursor family|BART]] [[microRNA]]s. These RNAs promote infected cells to proliferate, avoid attack by the host's immune system's [[cytotoxic T-cells]], and, possibly, block the infected cells' [[apoptosis]] (i.e. [[programmed cell death]]) response to injury (see [[Epstein-Barr virus-associated lymphoproliferative diseases#Epstein\u2013Barr virus infection|EBV infection]]).  \n\nThe predisposing conditions described in the previous paragraph can serve to enhance the ability of the plasmablasts in PBL to: avoid the host's [[Immune system#tumor immunology|immune surveillence]]; survive for prolonged periods, grow excessively, and acquire pro-malignant gene abnormalities. Some of the gene abnormalities found in PBL include: '''1)''' increased [[Gene expression|expression]]  of the ''[[MYC]]'' [[Oncogene#Proto-oncogene|proto-oncogene]] due to its rearrangement with an [[antibody]] gene by [[genetic recombination]] or, less commonly, other causes (Myc protein, the product of this gene, enhances cell proliferation, inhibits apoptosis, and promotes maliganancy); '''2)''' loss in the expression of the ''[[PRDM1]]'' gene whose product, PRDM1/BLMP1 protein, represses the expression of Myc protein;<ref name=\"pmid24319234\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ott G, Rosenwald A, Campo E | title = Understanding MYC-driven aggressive B-cell lymphomas: pathogenesis and classification | journal = Hematology. American Society of Hematology. Education Program | volume = 2013 | issue = | pages = 575\u201383 | date = 2013 | pmid = 24319234 | doi = 10.1182/asheducation-2013.1.575 | url = }}</ref>) '''3)''' frequent duplications in certain areas of [[chromosomes]] 1, 7, 11, and 22 (these duplications are similar to those often seen in diffuse large cell lymphoma)<ref name=\"pmid31494113\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Bhattacharyya S, ((Bains APS)), Sykes DL, Iverson BR, Sibgatullah R, Kuklani RM | title = Lymphoid neoplasms of the oral cavity with plasmablastic morphology-a case series and review of the literature | journal = Oral Surgery, Oral Medicine, Oral Pathology and Oral Radiology | volume = 128 | issue = 6 | pages = 651\u2013659 | date = December 2019 | pmid = 31494113 | doi = 10.1016/j.oooo.2019.08.001 | url = }}</ref>; '''4)''' reduced expression of at least 13 genes that are involved in B-cell responses to signaling agents.<ref name=\"pmid31725418\"/> '''5)''' increased expression of genes which promote the maturation of B-cells toward plasma cells (e.g. ''[[CD38]], [[CD138]], [[IR4|IR4/MUM1]], [[XBP1]], [[IL21R]]'', and, as just indicated, ''PRDM1''); and '''6)''' reduced expression of genes characteristic of B-cells (e.g. ''[[CD20]]'' and ''[[PAX5]]'').<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/>\n\n== Presentation ==\nPlasmablastic lymphoma lesions are most commonly rapidly growing, soft tissue masses<ref name=\"pmid29518976\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Dojcinov SD, Fend F, Quintanilla-Martinez L | title = EBV-Positive Lymphoproliferations of B- T- and NK-Cell Derivation in Non-Immunocompromised Hosts | journal = Pathogens (Basel, Switzerland) | volume = 7 | issue = 1 | pages = | date = March 2018 | pmid = 29518976 | pmc = 5874754 | doi = 10.3390/pathogens7010028 | url = }}</ref> that may be ulcerating, bleeding, and/or painful.<ref name=\"pmid29917262\"/> In a recent (2020) review of published cases, individuals presenting with PBD were typically middle-aged or elderly (range 1-88 years; median age 58 tears) males (~73% of cases).<ref name=\"pmid32269975\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Li YJ, Li JW, Chen KL, Li J, Zhong MZ, Liu XL, Yi PY, Zhou H | title = HIV-negative plasmablastic lymphoma: report of 8 cases and a comprehensive review of 394 published cases | journal = Blood Research | volume = 55 | issue = 1 | pages = 49\u201356 | date = March 2020 | pmid = 32269975 | doi = 10.5045/br.2020.55.1.49 | url = }}</ref> Only a few cases have been reported in pediatric cases.<ref name=\"pmid29917262\"/> The PDL lesions occurred most commonly in [[lymph node]]s (~23% of cases), the [[gastrointestinal tract]] (~18%), [[bone marrow]] (16%), and [[Mouth|oral cavity]] (12%).<ref name=\"pmid32269975\"/> Less frequently involved tissues include the skin, [[genitourinary tract]],<ref name=\"pmid32269975\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Li YJ, Li JW, Chen KL, Li J, Zhong MZ, Liu XL, Yi PY, Zhou H | title = HIV-negative plasmablastic lymphoma: report of 8 cases and a comprehensive review of 394 published cases | journal = Blood Research | volume = 55 | issue = 1 | pages = 49\u201356 | date = March 2020 | pmid = 32269975 | doi = 10.5045/br.2020.55.1.49 | url = }}</ref> [[paranasal sinuses]], lung, and bones.<ref name=\"pmid29518976\"/> While cases of PBL may present as a primary oral,<ref name=\"pmid31494113\"/> or, very rarely a skin<ref name=\"pmid27271843\"/> or lymph node<ref name=\"pmid31494113\"/> disease, most individuals present with a widespread [[Cancer staging#Overall stage grouping|stage III or IV]] disease which in ~40% of cases, is accompanied by systemic [[B-symptoms]] such as fever, [[night sweats]], and recent weight loss.<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/> Some 48%-63% of PBL cases occur in individuals with HIV/AIDS; ~80% of these HIV/AIDS-afflicted individuals have EBV+ disease whereas only ~50% of PBL individuals that do not have HIV/AIDS are EBV-positive.<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/> Individuals who develop PBL following organ transplantation are EBV-positive in >85% of cases.<ref name=\"pmid32269975\"/> Most post-transplant and HIV/AIDS patients have an extremely aggressive disease. However, patients whose major contributing factor to PBL-development is EBV-positivity often present with, and continue to have, a significantly less aggressive disease than other patients with PBL.<ref name=\"pmid29518976\"/> It is similarly clear that, on average, elderly patients (>68 years) likewise present with, and continue to have, a significantly less aggressive disease.<ref name=\"pmid22958176\"/> \n\n== Diagnosis == \nMicroscopic examination of involved PBD masses and infiltrates generally reveals diffuse proliferations of [[immunoblast]]-like cells with prominent features of plasma cells, i.e. plasmablastic cells.<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/> [[Immunostaining]] of these cells indicate that they lack B-cell marker proteins (e.g. CD20 and PAX5 [in ~10% of cases CD20 may be expressed at very low levels<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/>]) but rather express plasma cell marker proteins (e.g. ''CD38, CD138, IR4/MUM1, XBP1, IL21R'', and/or ''PRDM1''). The abnormalities in gene structures and expressions reported in the Pathophysiology section, particularly rearrangement and/or over expression of the ''MYC'' proto-oncogene, may also be apparent in these cells. The presence of HIV/AIDS or other causes of immuno-incompetence (see previous section), a history of having a low-grade lymphoma, and/or the presence of EVB+ plasmablasts in the disease's lesions would support the diagnosis of PBL.<ref name=\"pmid31725418\"/>\n\n=== Differential diagnosis ===\nVarious lymphomas can exhibit the microscopic appearance, including plasmablastic cells, and presentation of PBL. These lymphomas can usually be differentiated from PBL by further examinations of the plasmablasts for various marker proteins and determining other factors that favor the diagnosis of these lymphomas rather than PBL, as indicated in the following descriptions.   \n\n==== Anaplastic lymphoma kinase-positive large B-cell lymphoma ====\nUnlike PBL, the plasmablastic cells in anaplastic lymphoma kinase-positive large B-cell lymphoma strongly express products of the ''[[ACVRL1]]'' gene, i.e. activin receptor-like kinase 1 (ALK1) and are not infected with EBV and therefore do not express this virus's EBER or BART RNAs.<ref name=\"pmid31494113\"/>\n\n==== Human herpesvirus 8-positive diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, not otherwise specified ====\nUnlike PBL, the plasmablastic cells in human herpesvirus 8-positive diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, not otherwise specified express products of herpesvirus 8 (also termed Karposi sarcoma virus) such as [[LANA]]-1 protein. Also unlike PBL, these plasmablastic cells do not express CD30, CD138, CD79a,<ref name=\"pmid31725418\"/> or a clonal [[IgM]] antibody and usually are not EBV-infected and therefore usually do not express this virus's EBER or BART RNAs.<ref name=\"pmid31494113\"/>\n\n==== Primary effusion lymphoma ====\nIn contrast to PBL, the plasmablastic cells in primary effusion lymphomas, whether HHV8-positive or HHV8-negative, usually strongly express [[CD45]]<ref name=\"pmid31494113\"/> and in HHV8 cases express HHV8 proteins such as the LANA-1 protein. Primary effusion lymphoma, HH8-negative also differs from PBL in that its plasmablastic cells frequently express certain B-cell marker proteins such as CD20 and CD79a.<ref name=\"pmid31725418\"/> \n\n==== Plasmablastic plasma cell lymphoma ====\nVarious factors distinguish plasmablastic plasma cell lymphoma from PBL. Prior diagnosis of plasma cell lymphoma (i.e. [[multiple myeloma]] or [[plasmacytoma]]), the presence of [[Osteolytic lesion|lytic bone lesions]],<ref name=\"pmid31494113\"/> increased levels of serum calcium, renal insufficiency, and anemia, and the presence of a [[myeloma protein]] in the serum and/or urine favor the diagnosis of plasmablastic plasma cell lymphoma rather than plasmablastic myeloma. Ultimately however, the marker proteins expressed by the plasmablastic cells in the two diseases are almost identical and a diagnosis of \"plasmablastic neoplasm, consistent with PBL or multiple myeloma\" may be acceptable according to the current World Health Organization classification.<ref name=\"pmid31725418\"/>       \n\n==== Other B-cell lymphomas ====        \nThe plasmablastic cells in B-cell lymphomas, including diffuse B-cell lymphomas, chronic lymphocytic leukemia/small lymphocytic lymphoma, and follicular lymphoma generally express CD20 and often express [[CD45]] marker proteins. While PBL plasmablastic cells weakly express CD20 in 10% of cases, the strong expression of CD20 and the expression of CD45 virtually rules out PBL.<ref name=\"pmid31494113\"/>\n\n== Treatment and prognosis ==\nThe treatments for PBL have ranged from [[radiotherapy]] for localized disease to various chemotherapy regimens for extensive disease. The chemotherapy regimens have included [[CHOP]] (i.e. [[cyclophosphamide]], [[hydroxydoxorubicin]] (or [[doxorubicin]]), [[vincristine]], and either [[prednisone]] or [[prednisolone]]; CHOP-like regimens (e.g. CHOP plus [[etoposide]]); hyper-CVAD-MA (i.e. cyclophosphamide, vincristine, doxorubicin,  [[dexamethasone]] and high dose [[methotrexate]] and [[cytarabine]]); CODOX-M/IVAC (i.e. cyclophosphamide, vincristine, doxorubicin, high-dose methotrexate and [[ifosfamide]], [[etoposide]], and high-dose cytarabine); COMB (i.e. cyclophosphamide, [[oncovin]], [[methyl-CCNU]], and [[bleomycin]]); and infusional EPOCH (i.e. etoposide, prednisone, vincristine, cyclophosphamide, and doxorubicin). While the experience treating PBL with radiation alone has been limited, patients with localized disease have been treated with doxorubicin-based chemotherapy regimens plus radiotherapy. Overall, patients receiving one of the cited chemotherapy regimens have achieved [[disease-free survival]] and [[overall survival]] rates of 22 and 32 months, respectively. The [[National Comprehensive Cancer Network]] recommends the more intensive regimens (e.g. hyper-CVAD-MA or infusional EPOCH) to treat the disease. These regimens have attained 5 year overall and disease-free survivals of 38% and 40%, respectively. Too few patients have been treated with [[Hematopoietic stem cell#Autologous|autologous hematopoietic stem cell transplant]] in addition to chemotherapy for conclusions to be made. A few patients with HIV/AIDS-related PBL disease who were treated with [[Management of HIV/AIDS|highly active antiretroviral therapy (HAART)]] directed against the [[human immunodeficiency virus]] (i.e. HIV) have had remissions in their PDL lesions.<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/>\n\n=== Experimental treatments ===\nGiven the unsatisfactory results of standard chemotherapy regimens, new treatments are being explored for use in PBL. [[Bortezomib]], a drug that inhibits [[proteasome]]s, has been used alone or in combination with radiation and/or CHOP, EPOCH, or THP-COP ([[pirarubicin]], cyclophosphamide, vincristine, and prednisone) chemotherapy regimens to treat some scores of patients with newly diagnosed or relapsed PBL. The results of these exploratory studies have been at least modestly encouraging and provide strong support for further studies using more controlled conditions.<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/> A study sponsored by the AIDS Malignancy Consortium in collaboration with the [[National Cancer Institute]] is in its recruiting phase to study the dosages, safety, and efficacy of adding [[daratumumab]] to the EPOCH regimen in treating patients with PBL.<ref>https://clinicaltrials.gov/ct2/show/NCT04139304?cond=Plasmablastic+Lymphoma&draw=2&rank=1</ref> Daratumumab is a prepared [[monoclonal antibody]] that binds to CD38 and thereby directly or indirectly kills cells, including the plasmablasts in PBL, that express this marker protein on their surfaces.<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/> An ongoing study sponsored by the [[City of Hope Medical Center]] is examining the feasibility and safety of gene therapy that uses recombinant RNA to target a key element in the HIV genome in patients who have HIV/AIDs and a non-Hodgkins lymphoma, including patients with plasmablastic lymphoma.<ref>https://clinicaltrials.gov/ct2/show/NCT01961063?cond=Plasmablastic+Lymphoma&draw=2&rank=4</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Lymphoma]]\n* [[Epstein-Barr virus-associated lymphoproliferative diseases]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2|refs=\n}}\n\n[[Category:Lymphoma]]\n[[Category:Non-Hodgkin lymphoma]]\n[[:Category:Lymphoid-related cutaneous conditions]]\n[[Category:Epstein\u2013Barr virus-associated diseases]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS]]\n", "text_old": "\u2264'''Plasmablastic lymphoma''' (PBL) is a type of [[large B-cell lymphoma]] recognized by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) in 2017 as belonging to a subgroup of lymphomas termed [[lymphoid neoplasms with plasmablastic differentiation]]. The other lymphoid neoplasms within this subgroup are: [[Epstein-Barr virus-associated lymphoproliferative diseases#Epstein\u2013Barr virus-associated plasma cell|plasmablastic plasma cell lymphoma]] (or [[Epstein-Barr virus-associated lymphoproliferative diseases#Epstein\u2013Barr virus-associated plasma cell| plasmacytoma]]); [[Primary effusion lymphoma|primary effusion lymphoma, human herpes virus-positive or human herpes virus-negative]]; [[ALK+ large B-cell lymphoma|anaplastic lymphoma kinase-positive large B-cell lymphoma]]; and [[HHV-8-associated MCD|human herpesvirus 8-positive diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, not otherwise specified]]. All of these lymphomas are malignancies of plasmablasts, i.e. [[B-cells]] that have [[differentiated]] into plasmablasts but because of their [[malignant]] nature: fail to differentiate further into mature [[plasma cells]]; proliferate excessively; and accumulate in and injure various tissues and organs.<ref name=\"pmid31725418\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Chen BJ, Chuang SS | title = Lymphoid Neoplasms With Plasmablastic Differentiation: A Comprehensive Review and Diagnostic Approaches | journal = Advances in Anatomic Pathology | volume = 27 | issue = 2 | pages = 61\u201374 | date = March 2020 | pmid = 31725418 | doi = 10.1097/PAP.0000000000000253 | url = }}</ref>\n\nThe lymphomas in the lymphoid neoplasms with plasmablastic differentiation sub-group that are not PBL have sometimes been incorrectly considered to be variants of PBL. Each of the lymphomas in this subgroup of [[malignancies]] have distinctive clinical, morphological, and abnormal gene features. However, key features of these lymphomas sometime overlap with other lymphomas including those that are in this sub-group. In consequence, correctly diagnosing these lymphomas has been challenging.<ref name=\"pmid31360094\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Lopez A, Abrisqueta P | title = Plasmablastic lymphoma: current perspectives | journal = Blood and Lymphatic Cancer : Targets and Therapy | volume = 8 | issue = | pages = 63\u201370 | date = 2018 | pmid = 31360094 | pmc = 6467349 | doi = 10.2147/BLCTT.S142814 | url = }}</ref> Nonetheless, it is particularly important to diagnose them correctly because they can have very different prognoses and treatments than the lymphomas which they resemble.<ref name=\"pmid31725418\"/>  \n\nPlasmablastic lymphomas are aggressive and rare malignancies that usually respond poorly to [[chemotherapy]] and carry a very poor prognoses. They occur predominantly in males who have [[HIV/AIDS]], had a [[Organ transplantation|solid organ transplant]], or are [[Immunosuppression|immunosuppressed]] in other ways; ~5% of all individuals with PBL appear to be [[immunocompetent]], i.e. to have no apparent defect in their [[immune system]].<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/> The malignant plasmablasts in more than half the cases of PBL are infected with a potentially cancer-causing virus, [[Epstein Barr virus]] (EBV), and rare cases of PBL appear due to the  plasmablastic transformation of a preexisting a low-grade [[B-cell lymphoma]].<ref name=\"pmid27271843\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Korkolopoulou P, Vassilakopoulos T, Milionis V, Ioannou M | title = Recent Advances in Aggressive Large B-cell Lymphomas: A Comprehensive Review | journal = Advances in Anatomic Pathology | volume = 23 | issue = 4 | pages = 202\u201343 | date = July 2016 | pmid = 27271843 | doi = 10.1097/PAP.0000000000000117 | url = }}</ref> One variant of PBL, sometimes termed '''plasmablastic lymphoma of the elderly,''' has a significantly better prognosis than most other cases of PBL.<ref name=\"pmid22958176\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Liu F, Asano N, Tatematsu A, Oyama T, Kitamura K, Suzuki K, Yamamoto K, Sakamoto N, Taniwaki M, Kinoshita T, Nakamura S | title = Plasmablastic lymphoma of the elderly: a clinicopathological comparison with age-related Epstein-Barr virus-associated B cell lymphoproliferative disorder | journal = Histopathology | volume = 61 | issue = 6 | pages = 1183\u201397 | date = December 2012 | pmid = 22958176 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2559.2012.04339.x | url = }}</ref> The development of this variant appears due, at least in part, to [[immunosenescence]], i.e. the immunodeficiency occurring in old age.<ref name=\"pmid27271843\"/>   \n\n== History ==\nA study by Green and Eversole published in 1989<ref name=\"pmid2542861\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Green TL, Eversole LR | title = Oral lymphomas in HIV-infected patients: association with Epstein-Barr virus DNA | journal = Oral Surgery, Oral Medicine, and Oral Pathology | volume = 67 | issue = 4 | pages = 437\u201342 | date = April 1989 | pmid = 2542861 | doi = 10.1016/0030-4220(89)90388-5 | url = }}</ref> reported on 9 individuals afflicted with HIV/AIDS who \npresented with lymphomatous masses in the oral cavity; these lymphomas were populated by apparently malignant Epstein-Barr virus-infected plasmablasts; these cells did not express [[T-cell]] lymphocyte marker proteins. Eight years later, Delecluse and colleagues<ref name=\"pmid9028965\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Delecluse HJ, Anagnostopoulos I, Dallenbach F, Hummel M, Marafioti T, Schneider U, Huhn D, Schmidt-Westhausen A, Reichart PA, Gross U, Stein H | title = Plasmablastic lymphomas of the oral cavity: a new entity associated with the human immunodeficiency virus infection | journal = Blood | volume = 89 | issue = 4 | pages = 1413\u201320 | date = February 1997 | pmid = 9028965 | doi = | url = }}</ref> described a lymphoma, which they termed plasmablastic lymphoma, that had some features of a [[diffuse large B-cell lymphoma]] but unlike this lymphoma developed exclusively in the oral cavity, consisted of plasmablasts that lacked B-cell as well as T cell marker proteins and, in 15 of 16 cases, were infected with EBV. In 2008, the World Health Organization recognized this lymphoma as a variant of the diffuse large cell lymphomas.<ref name=\"pmid29917262\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Rodrigues-Fernandes CI, de Souza LL, ((Santos-Costa SFD)), ((Silva AMB)), ((Pontes HAR)), Lopes MA, de Almeida OP, Brennan PA, Fonseca FP | title = Clinicopathological analysis of oral plasmablastic lymphoma: A systematic review | journal = Journal of Oral Pathology & Medicine : Official Publication of the International Association of Oral Pathologists and the American Academy of Oral Pathology | volume = 47 | issue = 10 | pages = 915\u2013922 | date = November 2018 | pmid = 29917262 | doi = 10.1111/jop.12753 | url = }}</ref> Subsequent to this recognition, numerous studies found this lymphoma in wide range of tissues besides the oral cavity and in individuals with various other potentially predisposing immunodeficiency conditions.<ref name=\"pmid32269975\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Li YJ, Li JW, Chen KL, Li J, Zhong MZ, Liu XL, Yi PY, Zhou H | title = HIV-negative plasmablastic lymphoma: report of 8 cases and a comprehensive review of 394 published cases | journal = Blood Research | volume = 55 | issue = 1 | pages = 49\u201356 | date = March 2020 | pmid = 32269975 | doi = 10.5045/br.2020.55.1.49 | url = }}</ref> In 2017, this Organization classified PBL a the most common member of a rare subgroup of lymphomas termed lymphoid neoplasms with plasmablastic differentiation.<ref name=\"pmid31725418\"/>  \n\n== Pathopysiology ==\nIn addition to the immunodeficiency-causing viral disease, HIV/AIDS (it is an [[AIDS-defining clinical condition]]<ref name=\"pmid29518976\"/>), recent studies have diagnosed PBL in individuals who have one or more other causes for immunodeficiency.<ref name=\"pmid32269975\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Li YJ, Li JW, Chen KL, Li J, Zhong MZ, Liu XL, Yi PY, Zhou H | title = HIV-negative plasmablastic lymphoma: report of 8 cases and a comprehensive review of 394 published cases | journal = Blood Research | volume = 55 | issue = 1 | pages = 49\u201356 | date = March 2020 | pmid = 32269975 | doi = 10.5045/br.2020.55.1.49 | url = }}</ref> These causes include prior organ transplantation; [[immunosuppressive drug]]s; [[Autoimmune disease|autoimmune ]] and [[Inflammation#Inflammatory disorders|chronic inflammatory diseases]] (e.g. [[hepatitis C]]<ref name=\"pmid27271843\"/>, [[rheumatoid arthritis]], [[Graves' disease]], [[Giant-cell arteritis]], [[sarcoidosis]], and severe [[psoriasis]]) may also underlie development of PBL.<ref name=\"pmid28031174\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Tchernonog E, Faurie P, Coppo P, Monjanel H, Bonnet A, Algarte G\u00e9nin M, Mercier M, Dupuis J, Bijou F, Herbaux C, Delmer A, Fabiani B, Besson C, Le Gouill S, Gyan E, Laurent C, Ghesquieres H, Cartron G | title = Clinical characteristics and prognostic factors of plasmablastic lymphoma patients: analysis of 135 patients from the LYSA group | journal = Annals of Oncology | volume = 28 | issue = 4 | pages = 843\u2013848 | date = April 2017 | pmid = 28031174 | doi = 10.1093/annonc/mdw684 | url = }}</ref>); and immunosenescence due to age (e.g. >60 years). Rare cases of PDL have also occurred as a transformation of a low grade B-cell malignancy such as [[Chronic lymphocytic leukemia|chronic lymphocytic leukemia/small lymphocytic lymphoma]] or [[follicular lymphoma]].<ref name=\"pmid27687004\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Montes-Moreno S, Martinez-Magunacelaya N, Zecchini-Barrese T, Villambros\u00eda SG, Linares E, Ranchal T, Rodriguez-Pinilla M, Batlle A, Cereceda-Company L, Revert-Arce JB, Almaraz C, Piris MA | title = Plasmablastic lymphoma phenotype is determined by genetic alterations in MYC and PRDM1 | journal = Modern Pathology : an Official Journal of the United States and Canadian Academy of Pathology, Inc | volume = 30 | issue = 1 | pages = 85\u201394 | date = January 2017 | pmid = 27687004 | doi = 10.1038/modpathol.2016.162 | url = }}</ref> Studies also find that 60-75% of individuals diagnosed with PBL have [[Epstein-Barr virus]]-infected plasmablasts.<ref name=\"pmid31725418\"/> EBV infects ~95% of the world's population to cause [[asymptomatic|no symptoms]], minor [[non-specific symptoms]], or [[infectious mononucleosis]]. The [[virus]] then enters a [[Virus latency|latency]] phase in which infected individuals become lifetime [[asymptomatic carrier]]s of the virus in a set of their B-cells. Some weeks, months, years, or decades thereafter, a very small fraction of these carriers, particularly those with an [[immunodeficiency]], develop any one of various EBV-associated benign or [[malignant]] diseases, including, in extremely rare cases, [[Epstein\u2013Barr virus-associated lymphoproliferative diseases#Epstein\u2013Barr virus-positive plasmablastic lymphoma|Epstein\u2013Barr virus-positive plasmablastic lymphoma]].<ref name=\"pmid29885408\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Rezk SA, Zhao X, Weiss LM | title = Epstein\u2014Barr virus-associated lymphoid proliferations, a 2018 update | journal = Human Pathology | volume = 79| issue = | pages = 18\u201341| date = June 2018 | pmid = 29885408 | doi = 10.1016/j.humpath.2018.05.020 | url = }}</ref> The virus in infected plasmablastic cells appears to be in its [[Epstein-Barr virus-associated lymphoproliferative diseases#Epstein\u2013Barr virus infection|latency I phase]]; consequently, these infected cells express EBV products such as [[EBER]] [[Small nuclear RNA|nuclear RNAs]] and [[mir-BART2 microRNA precursor family|BART]] [[microRNA]]s. These RNAs promote infected cells to proliferate, avoid attack by the host's immune system's [[cytotoxic T-cells]], and, possibly, block the infected cells' [[apoptosis]] (i.e. [[programmed cell death]]) response to injury (see [[Epstein-Barr virus-associated lymphoproliferative diseases#Epstein\u2013Barr virus infection|EBV infection]]).  \n\nThe predisposing conditions described in the previous paragraph can serve to enhance the ability of the plasmablasts in PBL to: avoid the host's [[Immune system#tumor immunology|immune surveillence]]; survive for prolonged periods, grow excessively, and acquire pro-malignant gene abnormalities. Some of the gene abnormalities found in PBL include: '''1)''' increased [[Gene expression|expression]]  of the ''[[MYC]]'' [[Oncogene#Proto-oncogene|proto-oncogene]] due to its rearrangement with an [[antibody]] gene by [[genetic recombination]] or, less commonly, other causes (Myc protein, the product of this gene, enhances cell proliferation, inhibits apoptosis, and promotes maliganancy); '''2)''' loss in the expression of the ''[[PRDM1]]'' gene whose product, PRDM1/BLMP1 protein, represses the expression of Myc protein;<ref name=\"pmid24319234\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ott G, Rosenwald A, Campo E | title = Understanding MYC-driven aggressive B-cell lymphomas: pathogenesis and classification | journal = Hematology. American Society of Hematology. Education Program | volume = 2013 | issue = | pages = 575\u201383 | date = 2013 | pmid = 24319234 | doi = 10.1182/asheducation-2013.1.575 | url = }}</ref>) '''3)''' frequent duplications in certain areas of [[chromosomes]] 1, 7, 11, and 22 (these duplications are similar to those often seen in diffuse large cell lymphoma)<ref name=\"pmid31494113\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Bhattacharyya S, ((Bains APS)), Sykes DL, Iverson BR, Sibgatullah R, Kuklani RM | title = Lymphoid neoplasms of the oral cavity with plasmablastic morphology-a case series and review of the literature | journal = Oral Surgery, Oral Medicine, Oral Pathology and Oral Radiology | volume = 128 | issue = 6 | pages = 651\u2013659 | date = December 2019 | pmid = 31494113 | doi = 10.1016/j.oooo.2019.08.001 | url = }}</ref>; '''4)''' reduced expression of at least 13 genes that are involved in B-cell responses to signaling agents.<ref name=\"pmid31725418\"/> '''5)''' increased expression of genes which promote the maturation of B-cells toward plasma cells (e.g. ''[[CD38]], [[CD138]], [[IR4|IR4/MUM1]], [[XBP1]], [[IL21R]]'', and, as just indicated, ''PRDM1''); and '''6)''' reduced expression of genes characteristic of B-cells (e.g. ''[[CD20]]'' and ''[[PAX5]]'').<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/>\n\n== Presentation ==\nPlasmablastic lymphoma lesions are most commonly rapidly growing, soft tissue masses<ref name=\"pmid29518976\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Dojcinov SD, Fend F, Quintanilla-Martinez L | title = EBV-Positive Lymphoproliferations of B- T- and NK-Cell Derivation in Non-Immunocompromised Hosts | journal = Pathogens (Basel, Switzerland) | volume = 7 | issue = 1 | pages = | date = March 2018 | pmid = 29518976 | pmc = 5874754 | doi = 10.3390/pathogens7010028 | url = }}</ref> that may be ulcerating, bleeding, and/or painful.<ref name=\"pmid29917262\"/> In a recent (2020) review of published cases, individuals presenting with PBD were typically middle-aged or elderly (range 1-88 years; median age 58 tears) males (~73% of cases).<ref name=\"pmid32269975\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Li YJ, Li JW, Chen KL, Li J, Zhong MZ, Liu XL, Yi PY, Zhou H | title = HIV-negative plasmablastic lymphoma: report of 8 cases and a comprehensive review of 394 published cases | journal = Blood Research | volume = 55 | issue = 1 | pages = 49\u201356 | date = March 2020 | pmid = 32269975 | doi = 10.5045/br.2020.55.1.49 | url = }}</ref> (Only a few cases have been reported in pediatric cases.<ref name=\"pmid29917262\"/>) The PDL lesions occurred most commonly in [[lymph node]]s (~23% of cases), the [[gastrointestinal tract]] (~18%), [[bone marrow]] (16%), and [[Mouth|oral cavity]] (12%).<ref name=\"pmid32269975\"/> Less frequently involved tissues include the skin, [[genitourinary tract]],<ref name=\"pmid32269975\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Li YJ, Li JW, Chen KL, Li J, Zhong MZ, Liu XL, Yi PY, Zhou H | title = HIV-negative plasmablastic lymphoma: report of 8 cases and a comprehensive review of 394 published cases | journal = Blood Research | volume = 55 | issue = 1 | pages = 49\u201356 | date = March 2020 | pmid = 32269975 | doi = 10.5045/br.2020.55.1.49 | url = }}</ref> [[paranasal sinuses]], lung, and bones.<ref name=\"pmid29518976\"/> While cases of PBL may present as a primary oral,<ref name=\"pmid31494113\"/> or, very rarely a skin<ref name=\"pmid27271843\"/> or lymph node<ref name=\"pmid31494113\"/> disease, most individuals present with a widespread [[Cancer staging#Overall stage grouping|stage III or IV]] disease which in ~40% of cases, is accompanied by systemic [[B-symptoms]] such as fever, [[night sweats]], and recent weight loss.<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/> Some 48%-63% of PBL cases occur in individuals with HIV/AIDS; ~80% of these HIV/AIDS-afflicted individuals have EBV+ disease whereas only ~50% of PBL individuals that do not have HIV/AIDS are EBV-positive.<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/> Individuals who develop PBL following organ transplantation are EBV-positive in >85% of cases.<ref name=\"pmid32269975\"/> Most post-transplant and HIV/AIDS patients have an extremely aggressive disease. However, patients whose major contributing factor to PBL-development is EBV-positivity often present with, and continue to have, a significantly less aggressive disease than other patients with PBL.<ref name=\"pmid29518976\"/> It is similarly clear that, on average, elderly patients (>68 years) likewise present with, and continue to have, a significantly less aggressive disease.<ref name=\"pmid22958176\"/> \n\n== Diagnosis == \nMicroscopic examination of involved PBD masses and infiltrates generally reveals diffuse proliferations of [[immunoblast]]-like cells with prominent features of plasma cells, i.e. plasmablastic cells.<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/> [[Immunostaining]] of these cells indicate that they lack B-cell marker proteins (e.g. CD20 and PAX5 [in ~10% of cases CD20 may be expressed at very low levels<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/>]) but rather express plasma cell marker proteins (e.g. ''CD38, CD138, IR4/MUM1, XBP1, IL21R'', and/or ''PRDM1''. The abnormalities in gene structures and expressions reported in the Pathophysiology section, particularly rearrangement and/or over expression of the ''MYC'' proto-oncogene, may also be apparent in these cells. The presence of HIV/AIDS or other causes of immuno-incompetence (see previous section), a history of having a low-grade lymphoma, and/or the presence of EVB+ plasmablasts in the disease's lesions would support the diagnosis of PBL.<ref name=\"pmid31725418\"/>\n\n=== Differential diagnosis ===\nVarious lymphomas can exhibit the microscopic appearance, including plasmablastic cells, and presentation of PBL. These lymphomas can usually be differentiated from PBL by further examinations of the plasmablasts for various marker proteins and determining other factors that favor the diagnosis of these lymphomas rather than PBL, as indicated in the following descriptions.   \n\n==== Anaplastic lymphoma kinase-positive large B-cell lymphoma ====\nUnlike PBL, the plasmablastic cells in anaplastic lymphoma kinase-positive large B-cell lymphoma strongly express products of the ''[[ACVRL1]]'' gene, i.e. activin receptor-like kinase 1 (ALK1) and are not infected with EBV and therefore do not express this virus's EBER or BART RNAs.<ref name=\"pmid31494113\"/>\n\n==== Human herpesvirus 8-positive diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, not otherwise specified ====\nUnlike PBL, the plasmablastic cells in human herpesvirus 8-positive diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, not otherwise specified express products of herpesvirus 8 (also termed Karposi sarcoma virus) such as [[LANA]]-1 protein. Also unlike PBL, these plasmablastic cells do not express CD30, CD138, CD79a,<ref name=\"pmid31725418\"/> or a clonal [[IgM]] antibody and usually are not EBV-infected and therefore usually do not express this virus's EBER or BART RNAs.<ref name=\"pmid31494113\"/>\n\n==== Primary effusion lymphoma ====\nIn contrast to PBL, the plasmablastic cells in primary effusion lymphomas, whether HHV8-positive or HHV8-negative, usually strongly express [[CD45]]<ref name=\"pmid31494113\"/> and in HHV8 cases express HHV8 proteins such as the LANA-1 protein. Primary effusion lymphoma, HH8-negative also differs from PBL in that its plasmablastic cells frequently express certain B-cell marker proteins such as CD20 and CD79a.<ref name=\"pmid31725418\"/> \n\n==== Plasmablastic plasma cell lymphoma ====\nVarious factors distinguish plasmablastic plasma cell lymphoma from PBL. Prior diagnosis of plasma cell lymphoma (i.e. [[multiple myeloma]] or [[plasmacytoma]]), the presence of [[Osteolytic lesion|lytic bone lesions]],<ref name=\"pmid31494113\"/> increased levels of serum calcium, renal insufficiency, and anemia, and the presence of a [[myeloma protein]] in the serum and/or urine favor the diagnosis of plasmablastic plasma cell lymphoma rather than plasmablastic myeloma. Ultimately however, the marker proteins expressed by the plasmablastic cells in the two diseases are almost identical and a diagnosis of \"plasmablastic neoplasm, consistent with PBL or multiple myeloma\" may be acceptable according to the current World Health Organization classification.<ref name=\"pmid31725418\"/>       \n\n==== Other B-cell lymphomas ====        \nThe plasmablastic cells in B-cell lymphomas, including diffuse B-cell lymphomas, chronic lymphocytic leukemia/small lymphocytic lymphoma, and follicular lymphoma generally express CD20 and often express [[CD45]] marker proteins. While PBL plasmablastic cells weakly express CD20 in 10% of cases, the strong expression of CD20 and the expression of CD45 virtually rules out PBL.<ref name=\"pmid31494113\"/>\n\n== Treatment and prognosis ==\nThe treatments for PBL have ranged from [[radiotherapy]] for localized disease to various chemotherapy regimens for extensive disease. The chemotherapy regimens have included [[CHOP]] (i.e. [[cyclophosphamide]], [[hydroxydoxorubicin]] (or [[doxorubicin]]), [[vincristine]], and either [[prednisone]] or [[prednisolone]]; CHOP-like regimens (e.g. CHOP plus [[etoposide]]); hyper-CVAD-MA (i.e. cyclophosphamide, vincristine, doxorubicin,  [[dexamethasone]] and high dose [[methotrexate]] and [[cytarabine]]); CODOX-M/IVAC (i.e. cyclophosphamide, vincristine, doxorubicin, high-dose methotrexate and [[ifosfamide]], [[etoposide]], and high-dose cytarabine), COMB (i.e. cyclophosphamide, [[oncovin]], [[methyl-CCNU]], and [[bleomycin]]); and infusional EPOCH (i.e. etoposide, prednisone, vincristine, cyclophosphamide, and doxorubicin). While the experience treating PBL with radiation alone has been limited, patients with localized disease have been treated with doxorubicin-based chemotherapy regimens plus radiotherapy. Overall, patients receiving one of the cited chemotherapy regimens have achieved [[disease-free survival]] and [[overall survival]] rates of 22 and 32 months, respectively. The [[National Comprehensive Cancer Network]] recommends the more intensive regimens (e.g. hyper-CVAD-MA or infusional EPOCH) to treat the disease. These regimens have attained 5 year overall and disease-free survivals of 38% and 40%, respectively. Too few patients have been treated with [[Hematopoietic stem cell#Autologous|autologous hematopoietic stem cell transplant]] in addition to chemotherapy for conclusions to be made. A few patients with HIV/AIDS-related PBL disease who were treated with [[Management of HIV/AIDS|highly active antiretroviral therapy (HAART)]] directed against the [[human immunodeficiency virus]] (i.e. HIV) have had remissions in their PDL lesions.<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/>\n\n=== Experimental treatments ===\nGiven the unsatisfactory results of standard chemotherapy regimens, new treatments are being explored for use in PBL. [[Bortezomib]], a drug that inhibits [[proteasome]]s, has been used alone or in combination with radiation and/or CHOP, EPOCH, or THP-COP ([[pirarubicin]], cyclophosphamide, vincristine, and prednisone) chemotherapy regimens to treat some scores of patients with newly diagnosed or relapsed PBL. The results of these exploratory studies have been at least modestly encouraging and provide strong support for further studies using more controlled conditions.<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/> A study sponsored by the AIDS Malignancy Consortium in collaboration with the [[National Cancer Institute]] is in its recruiting phase to study the dosages, safety, and efficacy of adding [[daratumumab]] to the EPOCH regimen in treating patients with PBL.<ref>https://clinicaltrials.gov/ct2/show/NCT04139304?cond=Plasmablastic+Lymphoma&draw=2&rank=1</ref> Daratumumab is a prepared [[monoclonal antibody]] that binds to CD38 and thereby directly or indirectly kills cells, including the plasmablasts in PBL, that express this marker protein on their surfaces.<ref name=\"pmid31360094\"/> An ongoing study sponsored by the [[City of Hope Medical Center]] is examining the feasibility and safety of gene therapy that uses recombinant RNA to target a key element in the HIV genome in patients who have HIV/AIDs and a non-Hodgkins lymphoma, including patients with plasmablastic lymphoma.<ref>https://clinicaltrials.gov/ct2/show/NCT01961063?cond=Plasmablastic+Lymphoma&draw=2&rank=4</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Lymphoma]]\n* [[Epstein-Barr virus-associated lymphoproliferative diseases]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2|refs=\n}}\n\n[[Category:Lymphoma]]\n[[Category:Non-Hodgkin lymphoma]]\n[[:Category:Lymphoid-related cutaneous conditions]]\n[[Category:Epstein\u2013Barr virus-associated diseases]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS]]\n", "name_user": "Joflaher", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting my typos and clarifications of my text", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plasmablastic_lymphoma"}
{"title_page": "Anne (Dudley) Sutton", "text_new": "[[File:Harington Dudley family tree.jpg|thumb|right|Harington / Dudley family connections]]\n[[File:Anne (Dudley) Sutton.jpg|thumb|Henry Peacham, ''Minerva Britanna'' (London, 1612), p. 175]]\n'''Anne (Dudley) Sutton''' (1589-1615) was a companion of [[Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia]]\nShe was a daughter of [[Edward Sutton, 5th Baron Dudley]] and [[Theodosia Harington]].\n\nShe was known as \"Mrs Anne Dudley\" before her marriage.\n\nShe was a member of the household of Princess Elizabeth at [[Coombe Abbey]] with other young women including her cousin [[Elizabeth Dudley, Countess of L\u00f6wenstein|Elizabeth Dudley]], [[Anne Livingstone, Countess of Eglinton|Anne Livingstone]], [[William Bourchier, 3rd Earl of Bath|Frances Bourchier]], and [[Thomas Wharton (died 1622)|Philadelphia Carey]]. After Elizabeth married [[Frederick V of the Palatinate]] she went with her to [[Heidelberg Castle|Heidelberg]].<ref>[[Mary Anne Everett Green]], ''Elizabeth of Bohemia'' (London, 1909), pp. 9, 18, 44, 48, 96.</ref>\n\nIn 1612 an emblem published in [[Henry Peacham (born 1578)|Henry Peacham]]'s ''Minerva Brittana'' alluded to her steadfast qualities as alike to Diana the huntress, with a picture of [[Diana and Actaeon]], a verse, and an anagram on her in Italian \"e l'nuda Diana\".<ref>[https://archive.org/details/minervabritannao00peac/page/175 Henry Peacham, ''Minerva Britanna'' (London, 1612), p. 175].</ref> The intended allusion is to her labour and skills as a household administrator. The concept was derived from an emblem devised by Laurens van Haecht Goidtsenhoven.<ref>Judith Dundas, 'Imitation and Originality in Peacham's Emblems' in Bart Westerweel, ''Symbola et Emblemata'', vol. 8, 'Anglo-Dutch Relations in the Field of the Emblem' (Leiden, 1997), pp. 114-8.</ref>\n\nAnne with seven other ladies put their names in a hat to award kisses to winners at a tournament for [[Henry Frederick, Prince of Wales|Prince Henry]] in April 1612. The others included the [[Frances Carr, Countess of Somerset|Countess of Essex]], [[William Cecil, 2nd Earl of Salisbury|Lady Cranbourne]], [[Earl of Plymouth|Lady Windsor]], and [[Sir Lionel Tollemache, 2nd Baronet|Lady Stanhope]].<ref>A. B. Hinds, ''HMC Report on the Manuscripts of the Marquess of Downshire'', vol. 3 (London, 1938) p. 276 (The index suggests Theodosia Dudley rather than her daughter).</ref>\n\nAs a New Year gift in January 1613 and on the occasion of the marriage of Princess Elizabeth, Dudley received from [[Frederick V of the Palatinate]] a chain of pearls and a diamond worth 1,000 marks, (\u00a3666-13s-8d).<ref>A. B. Hinds, ''HMC Report on the Manuscripts of the Marquess of Downshire'', vol. 4 (London, 1940), p.2.</ref> [[John Chamberlain (letter writer)|John Chamberlain]] noted this gift as a single item, a chain of pearls and diamonds worth \u00a3500.<ref>Norman Egbert McClure, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.32106005854481&view=1up&seq=427 ''Letters of John Chamberlain'', vol. 1 (1931), p. 413.]</ref>\n\nAt the christening of [[Henry Frederick, Hereditary Prince of the Palatinate]] in March 1614 she received jewels worth \u00a3200.<ref>A. B. Hinds, ''HMC Report on the Manuscripts of the Marquess of Downshire'', vol. 4 (London, 1940), p.337.</ref>\n\nAnne married [[Hans Meinhard von Sch\u00f6nberg]], the [[Electorate of the Palatinate|Palatine]] Ambassador to England, and resident diplomat at Heidelberg, in London on 22 March 1615.<ref>Nadine Akkerman, ''The Correspondence of Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia'', vol. 1 (Oxford, 2015), p. 152.</ref> They were betrothed before 5 April 1614.<ref>Nadine Akkerman, ''The Correspondence of Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia'', vol. 1 (Oxford, 2015), p. 151.</ref> This was publicly known in June 1614.<ref>Folkestone Williams & [[Thomas Birch]], [https://archive.org/details/courtandtimesja00willgoog/page/n348 ''The Court and Times of James the First'', vol. 1 (London, 1848), p. 325.]</ref> In July it was known abroad they were in love.<ref>A. B. Hinds, ''HMC Report on the Manuscripts of the Marquess of Downshire'', vol. 4 (London, 1940), p. 445 & footnote.</ref> It had been said in London in December 1613 that Sch\u00f6nberg had come to England in part to entreat King James and [[Anne of Denmark]] not to recall Dudley from Heidelberg.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/courtandtimesja00willgoog/page/n306 ''The Court and Times of James the First'', vol. 1 (London, 1848), p. 283.]</ref> \n\nShe quarrelled with Elizabeth Apsley, a maid of honour and a distant cousin of [[Lucy Hutchinson]].<ref>[[Mary Anne Everett Green]], ''Elizabeth of Bohemia'' (London, 1909), pp. 418-9.</ref>\n\n[[James VI and I]] wrote to ask if a maid of honour could be a married woman in German custom, and what royal jewels were in her care. Elizabeth, the Electress, replied that Dudley only kept some silver plate, and also that her husband, Frederick V and his council had favoured the marriage.<ref>Mary Anne Everett Green, ''Elizabeth of Bohemia'' (London, 1909), p. 107.</ref>\n\nHer son was [[Frederick Schomberg, 1st Duke of Schomberg]].<ref>Nadine Akkerman, ''The Correspondence of Elizabeth Stuart Queen of Bohemia'', vol. 2 (Oxford, 2011), p. 1119.</ref> Anne died of a fever after giving birth to Frederick.<ref>''HMC Downshire'', vol. 5 (London, 1988), p. 379 nos. 784, 786, 787.</ref>\n\nIn her 1644 will her sister, [[Mary (Dudley) Sutton, Countess of Home]], left her nephew, Frederick Schomberg, a purse of gold coins.<ref>See the Countess of Home's will, \"Will of Maria Soton, Countess of Home\", The National Archives Prob/11/272/611 ff. 403-6, and National Library of Scotland MS. 14547.</reF>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dudley, Anne}}\n[[Category:1589 births]]\n[[Category:1615 deaths]]\n[[Category:Harington family]]\n[[Category:English ladies-in-waiting]]\n[[Category:16th-century English women]]\n[[Category:17th-century English women]]\n[[Category:Women of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:English courtiers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Harington Dudley family tree.jpg|thumb|right|Harington / Dudley family connections]]\n[[File:Anne (Dudley) Sutton.jpg|thumb|Henry Peacham, ''Minerva Britanna'' (London, 1612), p. 175]]\n'''Anne (Dudley) Sutton''' (1589-1615) was a companion of [[Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia]]\nShe was a daughter of [[Edward Sutton, 5th Baron Dudley]] and [[Theodosia Harington]].\n\nShe was known as \"Mrs Anne Dudley\" before her marriage.\n\nShe was a member of the household of Princess Elizabeth at [[Coombe Abbey]] with other young women including her cousin [[Elizabeth Dudley, Countess of L\u00f6wenstein|Elizabeth Dudley]], [[Anne Livingstone, Countess of Eglinton|Anne Livingstone]], [[William Bourchier, 3rd Earl of Bath|Frances Bourchier]], and [[|Thomas Wharton (died 1622)|Philadelphia Carey]]. After Elizabeth married [[Frederick V of the Palatinate]] she went with her to [[Heidelberg Castle|Heidelberg]].<ref>[[Mary Anne Everett Green]], ''Elizabeth of Bohemia'' (London, 1909), pp. 9, 18, 44, 48, 96.</ref>\n\nIn 1612 an emblem published in [[Henry Peacham (born 1578)|Henry Peacham]]'s ''Minerva Brittana'' alluded to her steadfast qualities as alike to Diana the huntress, with a picture of [[Diana and Actaeon]], a verse, and an anagram on her in Italian \"e l'nuda Diana\".<ref>[https://archive.org/details/minervabritannao00peac/page/175 Henry Peacham, ''Minerva Britanna'' (London, 1612), p. 175].</ref> The intended allusion is to her labour and skills as a household administrator. The concept was derived from an emblem devised by Laurens van Haecht Goidtsenhoven.<ref>Judith Dundas, 'Imitation and Originality in Peacham's Emblems' in Bart Westerweel, ''Symbola et Emblemata'', vol. 8, 'Anglo-Dutch Relations in the Field of the Emblem' (Leiden, 1997), pp. 114-8.</ref>\n\nAnne with seven other ladies put their names in a hat to award kisses to winners at a tournament for [[Henry Frederick, Prince of Wales|Prince Henry]] in April 1612. The others included the [[Frances Carr, Countess of Somerset|Countess of Essex]], [[William Cecil, 2nd Earl of Salisbury|Lady Cranbourne]], [[Earl of Plymouth|Lady Windsor]], and [[Sir Lionel Tollemache, 2nd Baronet|Lady Stanhope]].<ref>A. B. Hinds, ''HMC Report on the Manuscripts of the Marquess of Downshire'', vol. 3 (London, 1938) p. 276 (The index suggests Theodosia Dudley rather than her daughter).</ref>\n\nAs a New Year gift in January 1613 and on the occasion of the marriage of Princess Elizabeth, Dudley received from [[Frederick V of the Palatinate]] a chain of pearls and a diamond worth 1,000 marks, (\u00a3666-13s-8d).<ref>A. B. Hinds, ''HMC Report on the Manuscripts of the Marquess of Downshire'', vol. 4 (London, 1940), p.2.</ref> [[John Chamberlain (letter writer)|John Chamberlain]] noted this gift as a single item, a chain of pearls and diamonds worth \u00a3500.<ref>Norman Egbert McClure, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.32106005854481&view=1up&seq=427 ''Letters of John Chamberlain'', vol. 1 (1931), p. 413.]</ref>\n\nAt the christening of [[Henry Frederick, Hereditary Prince of the Palatinate]] in March 1614 she received jewels worth \u00a3200.<ref>A. B. Hinds, ''HMC Report on the Manuscripts of the Marquess of Downshire'', vol. 4 (London, 1940), p.337.</ref>\n\nAnne married [[Hans Meinhard von Sch\u00f6nberg]], the [[Electorate of the Palatinate|Palatine]] Ambassador to England, and resident diplomat at Heidelberg, in London on 22 March 1615.<ref>Nadine Akkerman, ''The Correspondence of Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia'', vol. 1 (Oxford, 2015), p. 152.</ref> They were betrothed before 5 April 1614.<ref>Nadine Akkerman, ''The Correspondence of Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia'', vol. 1 (Oxford, 2015), p. 151.</ref> This was publicly known in June 1614.<ref>Folkestone Williams & [[Thomas Birch]], [https://archive.org/details/courtandtimesja00willgoog/page/n348 ''The Court and Times of James the First'', vol. 1 (London, 1848), p. 325.]</ref> In July it was known abroad they were in love.<ref>A. B. Hinds, ''HMC Report on the Manuscripts of the Marquess of Downshire'', vol. 4 (London, 1940), p. 445 & footnote.</ref> It had been said in London in December 1613 that Sch\u00f6nberg had come to England in part to entreat King James and [[Anne of Denmark]] not to recall Dudley from Heidelberg.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/courtandtimesja00willgoog/page/n306 ''The Court and Times of James the First'', vol. 1 (London, 1848), p. 283.]</ref> \n\nShe quarrelled with Elizabeth Apsley, a maid of honour and a distant cousin of [[Lucy Hutchinson]].<ref>[[Mary Anne Everett Green]], ''Elizabeth of Bohemia'' (London, 1909), pp. 418-9.</ref>\n\n[[James VI and I]] wrote to ask if a maid of honour could be a married woman in German custom, and what royal jewels were in her care. Elizabeth, the Electress, replied that Dudley only kept some silver plate, and also that her husband, Frederick V and his council had favoured the marriage.<ref>Mary Anne Everett Green, ''Elizabeth of Bohemia'' (London, 1909), p. 107.</ref>\n\nHer son was [[Frederick Schomberg, 1st Duke of Schomberg]].<ref>Nadine Akkerman, ''The Correspondence of Elizabeth Stuart Queen of Bohemia'', vol. 2 (Oxford, 2011), p. 1119.</ref> Anne died of a fever after giving birth to Frederick.<ref>''HMC Downshire'', vol. 5 (London, 1988), p. 379 nos. 784, 786, 787.</ref>\n\nIn her 1644 will her sister, [[Mary (Dudley) Sutton, Countess of Home]], left her nephew, Frederick Schomberg, a purse of gold coins.<ref>See the Countess of Home's will, \"Will of Maria Soton, Countess of Home\", The National Archives Prob/11/272/611 ff. 403-6, and National Library of Scotland MS. 14547.</reF>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dudley, Anne}}\n[[Category:1589 births]]\n[[Category:1615 deaths]]\n[[Category:Harington family]]\n[[Category:English ladies-in-waiting]]\n[[Category:16th-century English women]]\n[[Category:17th-century English women]]\n[[Category:Women of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:English courtiers]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anne_(Dudley)_Sutton"}
{"title_page": "Jacksepticeye", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|Irish YouTuber}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name                 = Jacksepticeye\n| image                = Jacksepticeye by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption              = McLoughlin at [[PAX (event)|PAX]] West in 2018\n| channel_name         = Jacksepticeye\n| birth_name           = Se\u00e1n William McLoughlin\n| birth_date           = {{Birth date and age|1990|2|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place          = [[Ballycumber]], [[County Offaly]], [[Republic of Ireland]]<ref>{{Citation |title=How Well Does Jack Know America!? (YouTube video; Timestamp: 14:10) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ws2jlxXI28k&t=850s |language=en |access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.midlands103.com/midlandstoday/52492/ |title=\"He's Not A Native Of Athlone\" \u2013 Jacksepticeye's Mum |last=Croitor |first=Angel |date=October 2017 |website=Midlands 103 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111083250/http://www.midlands103.com/midlandstoday/52492/ |archive-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n| nationality          = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| residence            = [[Brighton]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| occupation           = {{flatlist|\n* [[YouTuber]]\n* [[actor]]\n}}\n| partner              = \n| website              = {{URL|jacksepticeye.com}}\n| signature            = \n| pseudonym            = {{flatlist|\n* Jacksepticeye\n* Jack\n* Jackaboy\n* Gaelic Gladiator<ref>https://twitter.com/Jack_Septic_Eye/</ref>\n* Toss Boy\n}}\n| years_active         = 2012\u2013present\n| genre                = {{flatlist|\n* [[Let's Play]]\n* [[comedy]]\n* [[vlog]]\n}}\n| associated_acts      = {{flatlist|\n* [[PewDiePie]]\n* ''[[Game Grumps]]''\n* [[Egoraptor]]\n* [[Markiplier]]\n* [[Emma Blackery]]\n* [[PJ Liguori]]\n* [[Ninja Sex Party]]\n* [[Jordan Maron]]\n* Team Edge\n* Cryaotic\n* Muyskerm\n* Lordminion777\n* CrankGameplays\n* Raised to the Ground\n}}\n| catchphrase(s)       = \"Top of the mornin' to ya laddies, my name is Jacksepticeye!\"\n| subscribers          = 23.7 million\n| views                = 12.45 billion\n| silver_button        = yes\n| silver_year          = 2014\n| gold_button          = yes\n| gold_year            = 2014\n| diamond_button       = yes\n| diamond_year         = 2016\n| stats_update         = April 7, 2020\n}}\n\n'''Se\u00e1n William McLoughlin''' (born 7 February 1990), better known as '''Jacksepticeye''', is an Irish [[YouTuber]] and actor, best known for his [[vlog]]s and comedic [[Let's Play]] series. {{as of|2020|3|df=}}, his channel has over 12 billion views and over 23 million subscribers, and is ranked the most-subscribed channel in Ireland.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://socialblade.com/youtube/top/country/ie/mostsubscribed |title=Top 250 YouTubers Channels in Ireland - Socialblade YouTube Stats {{!}} YouTube Statistics |website=socialblade.com |access-date=4 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCYzPXprvl5Y-Sf0g4vX-m6g |title=jacksepticeye |website=YouTube |url-status=live |access-date=15 December 2019}}</ref><!-- DO NOT ADD A PRECISE NUMBER OF SUBS; please take it to the talkpage if you want to debate this. Current consensus is to update every 100,000 subs (for example, '6.8 million'). --> McLoughlin has participated in fundraisers that have raised millions of US dollars for charity.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2019/03/21/jacksepticeye-charity-water-world-water-day/ |title=JackSepticEye To Headline Charity: Water Fundraising Stream For 'World Water Day' |last=Weiss |first=Geoff |date=21 March 2019 |website=Tubefilter |access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== 2012\u20132016: Start of YouTube career ===\nMcLoughlin joined YouTube on 24 February 2007 but didn't start uploading videos until November 2012 when he started to work on his channel under the name \"jacksepticeye\", posting gameplay videos. The origin of the name \"jacksepticeye\" started with his mother, who has always called him Jack, as it's a popular nickname for Sean in Ireland. A childhood friend found out about this and started to also call him Jack as a joke. One day he was playing football and he got accidentally hit in the eye, hard enough that it started bleeding. Over the next few weeks the eye got a bit infected and then his friend dubbed him 'Jack Septic Eye'.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wetheunicorns.com/youtubers/jacksepticeyes-name/ |title=What Is The Meaning Behind The Name JackSepticEye? |website=We The Unicorns |language=en |access-date=2019-07-16}}</ref> In 2013, McLoughlin was mentioned in a [[PewDiePie]] video, causing him to gain mass popularity; he went from 2,500 subscribers to 15,000 in four days.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news |last=O'Reilly |first=Quinton |url=http://www.thejournal.ie/irish-youtuber-popular-1722082-Oct2014/ |title=This Irish YouTuber went from 2,500 to 1.5 million subs in the space of a year |work=TheJournal.ie |access-date=8 May 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nDuring July 2014, McLoughlin's channel gained over 57 million views. At the time, his channel had only 800,000 subscribers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2014/08/29/top-100-most-viewed-youtube-gaming-channels-worldwide-july-2014/ |title=Top 100 Most Viewed YouTube Gaming Channels Worldwide \u2022 July 2014 |date=29 August 2014 |publisher=[[Tubefilter]] |access-date=29 June 2017}}</ref> By February 2015, the channel had reached one billion views and 3.2 million subscribers.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn January 2016, McLoughlin was one of the initial YouTubers signed under PewDiePie's network, Revelmode.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://teneightymagazine.com/2016/01/14/pewdiepie-launches-own-network/ |title=PewDiePie Launches Own Network \u2013 TenEighty \u2014 YouTube News, Features, and Interviews |website=teneightymagazine.com |language=en-GB |access-date=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/jan/13/youtube-pewdiepie-avengers-talent-squad-revelmode |title=YouTube star PewDiePie forms 'squad' to play games \u2013 and make them |last=Dredge |first=Stuart |date=13 January 2016 |website=the Guardian |language=en |access-date=26 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Early 2017: ''Scare PewDiePie'' controversy ===\n{{See also|PewDiePie#Media controversies, streaming, and formatted shows (2017\u22122018)}}\nMcLoughlin co-starred as the antagonist of the second season of the [[YouTube Red]] show ''[[Scare PewDiePie]]''. However, the season was cancelled before its release due to controversy surrounding PewDiePie.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/jacksepticeye-signs-with-wme-1203123765/ |title=YouTube Star and Gamer Jacksepticeye Signs With WME |last=Spangler |first=Todd |date=2019-01-30 |website=Variety |language=en |access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> The series was planned to premiere on 9 March 2017.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2017/03/13/pewdiepie-threatens-leak-scare-pewdiepie-season-2/ |title=PewDiePie Threatens To Leak Cancelled Second Season Of His YouTube Red Show |date=13 March 2017 |publisher=[[Tubefilter]] |access-date=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 February 2017, McLoughlin released a video called \"Let's Talk!\" to his YouTube channel which discussed [[PewDiePie]] being cut from [[Maker Studios]] for his use of [[anti-Semitic]] imagery. In it, he clarified that while he had tweeted in support of PewDiePie he did not condone his actions and believed he could have been more apologetic. Overall, McLoughlin states, \"You can still be friends with someone but not agree with something they do. I don't think the world is that black-and-white.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web |url=http://teneightymagazine.com/2017/02/22/jacksepticeye-clarifies-position-on-pewdiepie-controversy/ |title=Jacksepticeye Clarifies Position On PewDiePie Controversy \u2013 TenEighty \u2014 YouTube News, Features, and Interviews |website=teneightymagazine.com |language=en-GB |access-date=22 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the next day he tweeted that he regretted focusing on criticising PewDiePie in the video saying that he had been \"naive\". In a [[Tumblr]] post he said his main regret was not commenting on the mainstream media's reporting of the controversy stating, \"there were some unethical practices at play with the media, a lot of misquoting and misrepresentation.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nFollowing the controversy, it was confirmed that that the Revelmode network had been shut down by Disney.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2017/03/20/pewdiepie-revelmode-shutdown-worst-consequence/ |title=PewDiePie Calls Revelmode Shutdown \"Worst\" Consequence Of Anti-Semitic Controversy - Tubefilter |date=20 March 2017 |work=Tubefilter |access-date=26 May 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> McLoughlin then signed to the [[Disney Digital Network]].\n\n=== Mid 2017\u2013present: Other ventures and touring ===\nIn June 2017, Polaris, a division of [[Disney|The Walt Disney Company]], announced that McLoughlin would be featured on ''[[D XP|D {{vbar}} XP]]'', a television programming block on the channel [[Disney XD]]. The title of the series featuring McLoughlin is ''Polaris: Player Select''.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2017/06/15/disney-xd-maker-studios-jacksepticeye-parkergames-strawburry17-tv/ |title=Disney XD Taps Maker's Jacksepticeye, ParkerGames, Strawburry17 For Summer TV Block |date=15 June 2017 |publisher=[[Tubefilter]] |access-date=29 June 2017}}</ref> He and YouTuber [[Strawburry17]] hosted the Level Up! games panel at the [[D23 Expo|D23 Expo 2017]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sec.marketwatch.com/story/d23-expo-level-up-panel-showcases-the-walt-disney-companys-upcoming-games-line-up-2017-07-15 |title=D23 Expo Level Up! Panel Showcases The Walt Disney Company's Upcoming Games Line-Up |website=marketwatch.com |access-date=24 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet |number=883350234503421953?lang=en |user=disneyd23 |title=Just announced! @Jack_Septic_Eye and @Strawburry17 to host the Level Up! Games Panel at #D23Expo on Saturday, July 15, at 1pm.pic.twitter.com/cdETXHkeny |date=7 July 2017 |access-date=24 July 2017 |first=Disney |last=D23 |website=twitter.com}}</ref>  In July 2017, it was announced  that McLoughlin would be a playable character in the strategic prison-escape game ''[[The Escapists 2]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://teneightymagazine.com/2017/08/01/jacksepticeye-dantdm-and-inthelittlewood-are-in-a-game/ |title=JackSepticEye, DanTDM, and InTheLittleWood to Appear in Game \u2013 TenEighty \u2014 YouTube News, Features, and Interviews |website=teneightymagazine.com |language=en-GB |access-date=26 May 2018}}</ref> In September 2017, McLoughlin was featured on the [[RT\u00c92|RT\u00c9 2]] Rich List in the \"top 30 under 30\" category.<ref name=\":2\" /> McLoughlin toured throughout September\u2013October 2017, in the US with the ''How Did We Get Here'' tour, and then returned to the UK and Europe to tour with the [[Game Grumps]] for the ''Ready Player 3'' tour.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Pattison |first=Brynmor |url=https://www.irishmirror.ie/whats-on/arts-culture-news/jacksepticeye-tour-2017-irish-gaming-11171812 |title=Jacksepticeye tour 2017: Irish gaming YouTuber's dates |date=14 September 2017 |work=irishmirror |access-date=10 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, it was announced McLoughlin would produce exclusive content for [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] as part of a multi-year deal with Disney\u2019s Digital Network.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/platform/amp/2018/1/18/16903244/jacksepticeye-markiplier-to-produce-exclusive-content-for-twitch |title=Jacksepticeye, Markiplier and more gaming personalities to produce exclusive content for Twitch |website=www.polygon.com |language=en |access-date=21 April 2018}}</ref> In February 2018, McLoughlin released dates<ref>{{Citation |last=jacksepticeye |title=How Did We Get Here!? |date=16 February 2018 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=encyKIA_0B8 |access-date=10 May 2018}}</ref> for a US and Canada run of the ''How Did We Get Here'' tour.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://teneightymagazine.com/2018/05/01/jacksepticeye-announces-second-and-third-leg-of-americas-tour/ |title=JackSepticEye Announces Second And Third Leg Of American Tour \u2013 TenEighty \u2014 YouTube News, Features, and Interviews |website=teneightymagazine.com |language=en-GB |access-date=26 May 2018}}</ref> In April 2018, it was announced McLoughlin would be a part of the comedy line-up for the [[HowTheLightGetsIn Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ludlowadvertiser.co.uk/news/16192343.Laughter_line_up_revealed/ |title=Laughter line-up revealed |website=Ludlow Advertiser |language=en |access-date=30 April 2018}}</ref> In May 2018, McLoughlin uploaded a video of him and [[Ryan Reynolds]] playing the ''[[Deadpool (video game)|Deadpool]]'' video game.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://ew.com/gaming/2018/05/12/ryan-reynolds-deadpool-video-game/ |title=Watch Ryan Reynolds play the 'Deadpool' video game for first time |work=EW.com |access-date=12 May 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In January 2019, McLoughlin signed with [[William Morris Endeavor|WME]].<ref name=\":4\" /> In June 2019, it was announced that McLoughlin would be a part of the line-up at the Metarama Gaming + Music Festival alongside acts such as [[Marshmello]], [[Logic (rapper)|Logic]], [[Ninja (streamer)|Ninja]], and [[Overwatch League]] players.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8516587/metarama-festival-marshmello-logic-esports-lineup |title=Debut Metarama Festival Announces Marshmello, Logic and Esports Lineup |website=Billboard |access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/news/2019/06/19/ninja-dj-marshmello-play-las-vegas-video-game-and-music-festival/1498177001/ |title=Ninja, DJ Marshmello, Snoop Dogg, sign on for new video game-music festival in Las Vegas |website=USA TODAY |language=en |access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref>\n\n== YouTube content format ==\nMcLoughlin uploads once a day to his YouTube channel, usually a Let's Play or vlog style of video.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/top-irish-youtuber-details-rise-to-stardom-313859.html |title=Top Irish YouTuber details rise to stardom |last=\u00d3 F\u00e1tharta |first=Conall |date=21 February 2015 |website=[[Irish Examiner]] |access-date=11 December 2015}}</ref> McLoughlin has claimed an inclusive community is an important part of the Jacksepticeye channel stating \"one of the main things I wanted to do on YouTube is to keep people together\".<ref name=\":3\" /> McLoughlin calls himself the \"most energetic video-game commentator on YouTube\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/02/05/youtube-stars-money_n_6549906.html |title=YouTube Stars' Huge Earnings Will Make You Question All Your Life Choices |last=Beres |first=Damon |date=5 February 2015 |website=[[The Huffington Post]] |publisher=[[AOL Tech]] |access-date=11 December 2015}}</ref> McLoughlin has also described his content as an \"assault on the senses\" that people \"either love or hate\".<ref name=\":0\" /> In an interview with [[Irish Independent]] McLoughlin described the format of his videos as him playing and talking over video games, with a lot of swearing.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/games/if-i-ever-buy-a-lamborghini-someone-can-shoot-me-irish-youtube-millionaire-jacksepticeye-36127450.html |title='If I ever buy a Lamborghini, someone can shoot me' - Irish YouTube millionaire Jacksepticeye - Independent.ie |work=Independent.ie |access-date=22 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref> He has cited his use of swearing as a key aspect to his success saying, \"There\u2019s lots of swearing. The more you swear the better. People react very positively to that apparently.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news |last=Kelleher |first=Lynne |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/young-millionaire-swears-by-youtube-fktvbjkvs |title=Young millionaire swears by YouTube |date=13 September 2017 |work=The Times |access-date=22 April 2018 |language=en |issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism of YouTube ==\nMcLoughlin has been critical of the changing algorithms and policies at YouTube, voicing his dissatisfaction. In April 2018, McLoughlin responded to YouTube pulling ads from \"[[Censorship by Google#Advertiser-friendly content|unsuitable content]]\" stating \"This is people's careers. To completely switch how you do things and not tell anybody is a sh-ty {{sic}} thing to do.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2018/04/04/youtubers-say-crackdown-on-offensive-videos-has-gone-too-far/ |title=YouTubers say crackdown on offensive videos has gone too far |date=5 April 2018 |work=New York Post |access-date=22 April 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> In May 2018, McLoughlin responded to a surprise algorithm test from YouTube which changed the order of videos displayed in its subscription feed by stating that \"People use the subscription tab to mainly avoid this sort of algorithmic behavior... Please keep that to the home page and recommendations.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Foxx |first=Chris |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-44279189 |title=YouTube stars' fury over algorithm tests |date=28 May 2018 |work=BBC News |access-date=28 May 2018 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nIn December 2016, McLoughlin was a part of the [[Revelmode]] charity holiday livestream #Cringemas, with [[PewDiePie]], [[Markiplier]], [[Emma Blackery]] and [[PJ Liguori]]. The group raised over $1.3 million under the hashtag #EndAIDS, with matching donations from the [[Gates Foundation]] and YouTube.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.wetheunicorns.com/news/revelmode-raise-1-3-million-charity/ |title=Five YouTubers Raised $1.3 Million For Charity In The Weirdest Way Possible |work=We The Unicorns |access-date=22 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In December 2017, McLoughlin hosted two charity streams to raise money for [[Save The Children]], with Blackery and Liguori. In the second stream Blackery revealed that over $260,000 had been raised for the charity.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://teneightymagazine.com/2017/12/18/jacksepticeye-charity-stream-raises-over-260000/ |title=Jacksepticeye Charity Stream Raises Over $260,000 \u2013 TenEighty \u2014 YouTube News, Features, and Interviews |website=teneightymagazine.com |language=en-GB |access-date=22 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThroughout 2018, McLoughlin hosted various charity livestreams for charities such as the [[American Foundation for Suicide Prevention]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://teneightymagazine.com/2018/01/09/jacksepticeye-live-stream-raises-over-225000-for-charity/ |title=Jacksepticeye Live Stream Raises Over $225,000 for Charity \u2013 TenEighty \u2014 YouTube News, Features, and Interviews |website=teneightymagazine.com |language=en-GB |access-date=16 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.wetheunicorns.com/youtubers/jacksepticeye/response-charity-stream/ |title=JackSepticEye Had A $200,000 Response To Logan Paul |work=We Theorns |access-date=22 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref> the [[Depression and Bipolar Support Alliance]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://teneightymagazine.com/2018/03/03/jacksepticeye-raises-over-110000-with-charity-livestream/ |title=JackSepticEye Raises Over $110,000 With Charity Livestream \u2013 TenEighty \u2014 YouTube News, Features, and Interviews |website=teneightymagazine.com |language=en-GB |access-date=16 April 2018}}</ref> GameChanger,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://teneightymagazine.com/2018/05/05/jacksepticeye-live-stream-raises-over-150000-for-charity/ |title=JackSepticEye Live Stream Raises Over $150,000 For Charity \u2013 TenEighty \u2014 YouTube News, Features, and Interviews |website=teneightymagazine.com |language=en-GB |access-date=8 May 2018}}</ref> a charity with the stated aim of \"[leveraging] technology and innovation to empower patients to play, learn, and socialize\",<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://gamechangercharity.org/ |title=GameChanger Charity |website=Game Changer Charity}}</ref> AbleGamers, a charity which creates custom gaming setups for disabled gamers, [[St. Jude Children's Research Hospital]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wetheunicorns.com/youtubers/jacksepticeye/charity-livestream-fortnite/ |title=JackSepticEye Just Raised An INCREDIBLE Amount Of Money For Charity |work=We The Unicorns |access-date=2018-12-01 |language=en}}</ref> and [[Crisis Text Line]] raising a total of over $1 million for charities in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://teneightymagazine.com/2018/12/15/jacksepticeye-raises-over-1-million-for-charity-in-2018/ |title=Jacksepticeye Raises Over $1 Million For Charity in 2018 \u2013 TenEighty \u2014 YouTube News, Features, and Interviews |language=en-GB |access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, McLoughlin hosted a livestream which raised over $100,000 for the [[Make-A-Wish Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://teneightymagazine.com/2019/02/01/jacksepticeye-hosts-january-livestream-for-make-a-wish-foundation/ |title=Jacksepticeye Hosts January Livestream for Make-a-Wish Foundation \u2013 TenEighty \u2014 YouTube News, Features, and Interviews |language=en-GB |access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref> In May, McLoughlin hosted a fundraising stream for [[Red Nose Day 2019]] raising over $110,000 in nine hours.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://fundraising.co.uk/2019/05/02/youtuber-raises-110k-in-9-hours-in-us-red-nose-day-livestream/ |title=YouTuber raises $110K in 9 hours in US Red Nose Day livestream |last=May |first=Melanie |date=2019-05-02 |website=UK Fundraising |language=en-GB |access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref> In January 2020, McLoughlin hosted a livestream which raised over $200,000 in four hours for the [[bushfires in Australia]]. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/01/26/youtuber-jacksepticeye-raises-200000-four-hours-australian-bushfires-12123822/ |title=YouTuber JackSepticEye raises $200,000 in under four hours for Australian bushfires |website=metro.co.uk |access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> In April 2020, McLoughlin hosted a livestream which raised over $650,000 in 12 hours for [[COVID-19]] relief funds.<ref name=\"HopeFromHomeCNN\">{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/04/09/us/home-from-home-charity-livestream-trnd/index.html|title=A YouTube gamer helped raise nearly $660,000 in 12 hours for Covid-19 relief efforts|first=Austen|last=Bundy|work=CNN|date=April 9, 2020|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Including subsequent livestreams in collaboration with McLoughlin, the campaign raised over $1.7 million.<ref name=\"HopeFromHomeCNN\"/> As of January 2020, since 2017, McLoughlin has raised almost $4 million in total in charity livestreams.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tiltify.com/@jacksepticeye/profile |title=@jacksepticeye profile on tiltify |website=tiltify.com |access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMcLoughlin grew up in [[Athlone]], Ireland where he was given the nickname Jacksepticeye. Whilst at college, McLoughlin was the drummer for the metal band, Raised to the Ground, with whom he released one EP, ''Risen from the Ashes'', in 2009.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.altpress.com/features/music_youtube_stars_listen_to/ |title=Here's what some of the top YouTubers listen to |date=27 June 2017 |magazine=[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]] |access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://gazettereview.com/2017/07/jacksepticeye-net-worth-rich-youtube-celebrity-gamer/ |title=Jacksepticeye Net Worth 2018 \u2013 How Rich is the YouTube Celebrity Gamer |date=16 August 2017 |publisher=Gazette Review |access-date=16 August 2018}}</ref> He currently lives in [[Brighton]], England. In October 2018, McLoughlin announced that he had split from his Danish vlogger girlfriend Signe Hansen, better known as \"Wiishu\". He posted on [[Twitter]] that it was \"not an easy decision to make\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/newsbeat-45807559 |title=YouTubers Jacksepticye and Wiishu confirm 'emotional' split |access-date=10 October 2018 |work=BBC News}}</ref> In March 2019, McLoughlin announced that he is currently in a relationship with Dutch YouTuber Evelien Smolders, formerly known as \"GirlGamerGab\" but now better known as \"Gab Smolders\".<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/BvCALUml697/</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Film ===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Free Guy]]''\n|Q*Bert<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dotesports.com/streaming/news/ninja-jacksepticeye-pokimane-and-more-will-co-star-in-ryan-reynolds-free-guy |title=Ninja, Jacksepticeye, Pokimane and more will co-star in Ryan Reynolds' Free Guy |last=Walker |first=Ben |website=Dot Esports |access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n|Post-production\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Air date\n!Show\n!Channel\n!Role\n!{{abbr|Refs|References}}\n|-\n|2017\n|''Polaris: Player Select''\n|[[Disney XD]]\n|Himself\n|<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wetheunicorns.com/news/jacksepticeye-disney-channel-tv-show/ |title=JackSepticEye Is Getting A Disney Channel TV Show! |website=We The Unicorns |language=en |access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[The Late Late Show (Irish TV series)|The Late Late Show]]''\n|[[RT\u00c9 One]]\n|Guest\n|<ref>{{Cite journal |date=2018-02-24 |title=Jacksepticeye and Jane Anne melt hearts on Late Late |url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2018/0224/943208-jacksepticeye-and-jane-anne-melt-hearts-on-late-late/ |language=en}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Web series===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n!{{abbr|Refs|References}}\n|-\n| 2015-16\n| ''[[Did You Know Gaming?]]''\n| Himself (voice)\n| Narrated 2 episodes\n|<ref>{{Citation |last=DidYouKnowGaming? |title=Shadow of the Colossus - Did You Know Gaming? Feat. Jacksepticeye |date=2016-08-20 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sv4LtoYoHSE |access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=DidYouKnowGaming? |title=Five Nights at Freddy's & The Fake FNAF 4 Ft. Jacksepticeye - Did You Know Gaming? |date=2015-08-08 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EIobzSH8ITQ |access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Youtube Rewind]]''\n| Himself\n| Also was asked to take part in 2017 and 2018, but refused the offer{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://teneightymagazine.com/2016/12/07/youtubers-star-in-youtube-rewind-2016/ |title=UK YouTubers Star In YouTube Rewind 2016 \u2013 TenEighty \u2014 YouTube News, Features, and Interviews |language=en-GB |access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Good Mythical Morning]]''\n| Himself\n| Also appeared in ''Good Mythical More''\n|<ref>{{Citation |last=Good Mythical Morning |title=Tasting Nasty Video Game Food ft. JACKSEPTICEYE |date=2018-09-11 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DgTJ3-WMAWY |access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Good Mythical MORE |title=LET'S PLAY: Overcooked 2 ft. JACKSEPTICEYE |date=2018-09-11 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ls9Sfn5R5LI |access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref>\n|-\n| Cancelled\n| ''[[Scare PewDiePie]]'' (Season 2)\n| Himself\n|[[YouTube Red]]\n|<ref name=\":4\" />\n|}\n\n== Gameography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Platforms\n! Role\n!{{abbr|Refs|References}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2017\n| ''[[Pinstripe (video game)|Pinstripe]]''\n| rowspan=3 | [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Linux]], [[macOS]]\n| Drunk Man 2 \"Jack\"\n|<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/3/12/18262008/pewdiepie-tseries-game-youtube-sub-bots-algorithm |title=PewDiePie's battle for largest YouTube channel is now an indie video game |last=Alexander |first=Julia |date=2019-03-12 |website=The Verge |access-